      <chapter xml:id="ch-intro">
        <title>Introduction: What is this for?</title>
        <p>
          The goal for this textbook is that it be different.
          Though many familiar topics will be explored, the person thinking along with this book
          will, with luck and commitment, work their way towards a different view of the world
          as it now exists. Ideally, the person thinking along with this book will find themselves
          committed to radical restructuring of the existing world order, which, in the opinion of this
          book<rsq/>s author, is monstrously wasteful of human potential, ecocidal towards human and
          nonhuman life, disruptive of unique and fascinating natural processes, stiflingly unfree and 
          cramped in its practices and beliefs.        
          Mathematics and its associated fields (statistics, data science, computer science,
          and so on) are often used to describe or predict the world. This is no longer enough. 
          The point is to change the world. The hope, and the wager, is that an approach to 
          some basic and fundamental mathematical ideas can equip and energize the reader, that is, you, 
          for that beautiful, important, and ennobling task.
        </p>
        <axiom xml:id="axiom-recognition-with-math">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Quantitative reasoning, often called mathematics, is a 
              millennia-spanning human project across radically different
              cultures aimed at describing, predicting, and changing the
              world.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </axiom>

        <p>
          The French thinker Jacques Ranciere wrote a fascinating book,
          <pubtitle>The Ignorant Schoolmaster</pubtitle> about the
          French educator Joseph Jacotot. To radically oversimplify the point:
          Jacotot believed that all humans are equally intelligent and that
          explanation and lecture could often serve the purpose of 
          <q>stultifying</q>. That is, there is real cost in striving to skip
          past the struggle to understand by way of an explanation from a
          so-called authority in the subject. A powerful and challenging thought!
          Though this author will not now cease writing, and thus will be in 
          some violation of Jacotot<rsq/>s ideas (or at least Ranciere<rsq/>s
          rendering of Jacotot<rsq/>s ideas). Still:
        </p>
        <axiom xml:id="axiom-learning">
          <statement>
            <p>
              The learner must do the learning.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </axiom>
        <axiom xml:id="axiom-teacher">
          <statement>
            <p>
              The only teacher is the learner.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </axiom>        
        <axiom xml:id="axiom-teacher-other-learners">
          <statement>
            <p>
              The learner-who-is-also-the-teacher will often benefit by 
              learning with other learners.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </axiom>        
        <axiom xml:id="axiom-intuition-supplement">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Mathematical thinking is a powerful supplement to human intuition.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </axiom>        
        <axiom xml:id="axiom-intuitive-math">
          <statement>
            <p>
              Wherever possible, mathematical ideas should be grounded in human 
              intuition.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </axiom>
      </chapter>      

      <chapter xml:id="ch-preliminaries">
        <title>Some Preliminary Concepts</title>
        <p>
          A few general mathematical ideas might help us down the line. 
          <definition xml:id="def-function">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A <term>function</term> is a mathematical rule which
                receives an input (often a number or list of numbers)
                and returns an output
                (often a number) in a consistent way. That is, for each 
                particular legitimate input the function will produce the
                same output. 
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          The notation for functions is often what can cause a bit of
          confusion for the new mathematical thinker. It is often, when
          possible, written as a formula, but with notation that mixes
          some meaning with the way mathematical notation usually works.
          Specifically, one often sees a function <m>f</m> defined like so:
          <me>
            f(x)=5x+3
          </me>
          Please try to suppress any negative emotions associated with such 
          an expression. The problem is (and we who have become used to the
          notation sometimes forget this) that by the time someone sees this
          notation, they have generally been told that when one sees a 
          character next to an open parenthesis, <q>(</q>, that this should
          be understood as implying multiplication. Yet this is absolutely
          not what is going on in this mathematical expression. Instead, we
          are to understand (somehow) that <m>f</m> is a function, and the 
          input for that function is to be understood as <m>x</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          More specifically, this expression:
          <me>
            f(x)=5x+3
          </me>
          is attempting to communicate the following information
          about this function. 
          <q>
            This function, when passed some
            numerical value, will first multiply that value
            by five, and then will take that result and add
            three to it. This number will be passed back
            to whoever input that original numerical value.
          </q>
          Another way to say this is that <m>x</m> is really just
          a way to allow us to <q>fill in the blanks</q>. We might also
          write this function like so:
          <me>
            f(\underline{~~~})=5(\underline{~~~})+3
          </me>
          This sort of filling-in-the-blanks becomes cumbersome for 
          more complex rules, though, so we use <m>x</m> instead. Another
          way we could, even more clumsily, write it would be:
          <me>
            f(\text{whatever number is here})=5(\text{that number also goes here})+3
          </me>
          Before we move on, perhaps it would be good to be specific:
          <me>
            f(2)=5(2)+3=10+3=13
          </me>
          <me>
            f(3)=5(3)+3=15+3=18
          </me>
          <me>
            f(-3)=5(-3)+3=-15+3=-12
          </me>
          <me>
            f(100)=5(100)+3=500+3=503
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          Mainly, when working with a function, try to remember that
          it is just a way of telling you how to fill in the blanks.
        </p>
      </chapter>

