          <section xml:id="sec-representation-paradoxes">
            <title>Paradoxes</title>
            <introduction>
              <p>
                We will explore two more methods of apportionment. But why? Are not
                two methods already one more than we need? This is another occasion
                where we can learn from unexpected behaviors of complex systems.
                What if we designed a system, using our intuition, to accomplish
                a task, but then we find that in practice, despite our care in 
                designing the system, we find unexpected possible outcomes, possibly
                even outcomes that offend our intuition about how the system behaves?
                This sort of behavior is sometimes called a <term>paradox</term>. 
                Though the use of this term in cases like this is slightly at odds with 
                its technical and historical meaning in logic and philosophy, we will 
                retain it to mean, for us, 
                <q>
                  behaviors that our system exhibit but which offend our sense of
                  how the system ought, based on our intended design, to behave
                </q>.
              </p>
              <p>
                We will consider three examples from US history,
                The Alabama Paradox, the Population Paradox, and the New State Paradox.
              </p>
            </introduction>
