      <chapter xml:id="ch-weighted-voting">
        <title>Power in Weighted Voting Systems</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            All of the effort put into the systems described in 
            the previous chapter were premised upon an
            intuitive idea: that if a state has, for example, 
            twice the representatives, then it will have
            twice the power in the House of Representatives. But 
            remember: one of the overarching themes of
            this book is that we want to be able to use 
            mathematics and its related fields to investigate 
            whether our intuitive ideas about how things 
            work are, in fact, accurate. We have already seen
            some examples of how this can happen. But the 
            belief related to this idea of power is quite
            surprising and can be motivated with a 
            relatively simple example.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <section xml:id="formalizing-weighted">
          <title>A Motivating Example and Formalizing Weighted Voting</title>
          <example xml:id="ex-weighted-intuition">
            <title>Intuition Misleading Us?</title>
            <p>
              Suppose there were three states in the 
              nation with populations such that, 
              in the 100-member House
              of Representatives, one state, Alsaka, had 49 representatives, 
              one state, Bartleby, had 47 representatives, and a third
              state, Cropland, had four representatives. 
              Let us further assume that these numbers of representatives are
              proportional to population. 
              (For example, this would be exactly true if the populations were 49,000, 
              47,000, and 4000, respectively.) 
              So according to the intuition we have
              been basing our work on up until now, 
              this system has been constructed 
              in a way that is fair. It has explicitly 
              and exactly matched the proportion of 
              numbers of representatives to the proportion 
              of the number of people in the
              population for each state. 
              The state that has 49% of the population has
              49% of the representatives, the state that 
              has 47% of the population has 47% of
              the representatives, and the state that 
              has 4% of the population has 4% of 
              the representatives.
              (If you look back at examples and exercises from 
              <xref ref="ch-democracy-representation"/> you will notice that in practice
              it will almost never happen that these proportions match so exactly. We have, 
              in a sense, imagined what seems to be a rather ideal situation for fairness
              in the proportional representation of these states in this legislative body.)
              Our intuition has told us and our justification for all
              the work in <xref ref="ch-democracy-representation"/> is based on the idea that
              this should preserve those proportions, as well, in terms of decision-making
              power. That is, if you have 49% of the representatives, you should have
              roughly 49% of the decision-making power, similarly 47% of the representatives
              should give you 47% of the decision-making power, and 4% of the representatives
              should give you 4% of the decision-making power.
            </p>
            <p>
              Before we proceed further, if you were to guess how powerful each state was
              in the legislature, what would you say? Does it match the percentages
              described above? Or is the state with 49,000 people twice
              as powerful as the state with 4000 people? Five times as powerful? (Note: you
              should not feel bad if you have only a vague sense of this. <q>Power</q> is
              a concept that we have not carefully defined. Indeed, that is the point of this
              section, to develop a coherent approach to thinking mathematically about 
              how power might be quantified in such situations.)
            </p>
            <p>
              So let us suppose that these states have quite distinct populations and, further,
              let us suppose that each state delegation is disciplined and loyal and always
              votes together as a group. (If you think this changes your idea of the power of
              each state, that seems reasonable to me. Interesting how quickly assumptions
              and constraints change our ideas about how a system works, no?)
            </p>
            <p>
              How do things play out? Well let us think it through: Suppose the proposed
              measure that this legislative body is deliberating upon is whether to 
              locate a (necessary?) toxic
              waste dump in Cropland. We might expect this to be approved by the 49
              representatives from Alsaka and the 47 from Bartleby, which would allow
              the measure to pass by majority vote. (Note that there is another assumption
              here, one we might do well to (re)consider later, namely that simple majority,
              which in this case would be 51 out of 100, is all that is needed to
              pass a measure.) Obviously 96 votes will suffice to pass the measure.
              That is to say: if both Alsaka and Bartleby favor a measure, then that 
              measure will be approved by the legislative body. 
            </p>
            <p>
              But suppose, instead, that a measure were introduced to place the 
              waste dump in Alsaka? Why, then we might expect that Bartleby and
              Cropland could agree to vote in favor of this measure, which would
              thus pass by a 51 to 49 count. A measure passed by 51 to 49 is just as
              binding as a measure passed by 96 to 4. This fact turns out to have
              a rather interesting consequence. In fact, we can now notice the 
              following key fact: 
              <em>
                If two of the three states are in favor of a measure, then
                the measure will pass.
              </em>
              This may be quite surprising, even disturbing. Especially since
              it shows that our intuition about the scaling of representatives
              to population might completely fail to scale the decision-making
              power in the way we had hoped. Alsaka has the same amount of 
              power in this system as Cropland does, despite the fact that its
              population is over 12 times bigger. A citizen of Alsaka has 
              less than 
              <m>
                \frac{1}{12}
              </m>
              the amount of power as a citizen of Cropland. It is not unreasonable
              to think that over time this sort of distortion away from 
              <q>equal representation</q> might have rather significant effects
              upon the views citizens might have of the legitimacy of the 
              political system.
            </p>
            <p>
              Note that we have different ways we might think of the power
              in this system and how it is distributed. Based on previous
              ways we have been thinking about such things, we might
              choose to think of there being 100% of power that must be 
              distributed. Then in this case we would say that each 
              state has roughly 33.3% of the power. We could similarly 
              declare that all the power adds to 1 and say that each
              state has power measured at 0.333. 
            </p>
            <aside>
              <p>
                There is nothing preventing us from declaring there to be
                any amount of power which must be distributed. We might 
                set up our analysis such that 45 <q>power units</q> are 
                available to be distributed in the system. Then our analysis
                would conclude in this case that each state has 15 power
                units. But can you see how this is really just introducing a
                rather arbitrary additional number into the process? Is this
                not rather less illuminating to say that Cropland has 15
                of the 45 power units? It is easier just to say it has 33.3%
                of the power or 0.333 of the power.
              </p>
            </aside>
          </example>
          <p>
            Before we move on to a more systematic approach to computing power
            within a system like this, let us first notice how sensitive such 
            a system might be to changes in the conditions of the population.
          </p>
          <example>
            <p>
              Suppose a decade passes, and during that time
              1500 people move from State Bartleby to Alsaka and 
              500 from Cropland to Alsaka (but all other births and deaths
              cancel out so the only changes are these relocations). Now what?
            </p>

          </example>
          <p>
            In a rather beautiful demonstration of the fact that math and
            quantitative reasoning are creative processes, there are two 
            main approaches to computing the power available to each state
            in a system like this. The numbers they produce are sometimes the
            same but often are not. Each conceives of what matters in a different
            way, which we will summarize as the power in saying no and the 
            power in saying yes.
          </p>
          <p>
            One final task before we begin: the terminology and assumptions
            we will use throughout the following analysis. To achieve a sort 
            of generality of application, we will abstract slightly from the 
            descriptions above. Rather than states we will think of 
            <term>players</term> in a <term>weighted voting system</term>. 
            Each player will have a <term>weight</term>, and the system
            itself will have a <term>quota</term>, which is the required
            total weight of players required to pass a measure.
          </p>
          <p>
            To make this clear, in <xref ref="ex-weighted-intuition"/>, 
            there are
            three players, Alsaka with weight 49, Bartleby with weight 47, 
            and Cropland with weight 4. The quota in that example is 51. We 
            always require that the quota exceed half the total weight of the 
            system. (Why must we insist on this? How would the system potentially
            break down if we failed to require this?) Our notation for such a
            system will be: 
            <me>
              [51:49,47,4]  
            </me>
            We will always write the weights in descending order after the colon.
            More generally if we have <m>n</m> players, <m>P_1, P_2, \dots, P_n</m>
            with weights (in descending order)  <m>w_1, w_2, \dots, w_n</m> and 
            quota <m>q</m>, we will denote this weighted voting system as:
            <me>
              [q:w_1,w_2,\dots,w_n]
            </me>
          </p>
        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-no-power">
          <title>The Power of No</title>
          <p>
            Our purpose in this section is to explore how we might measure
            power in a weighted voting system by the ability to say 
            <q>No!</q> to a measure and for that <q>No!</q> to matter. An 
            easy first step is to say that if it were impossible that a 
            <q>No!</q> from some player could matter, then this player
            has no power in the system. We might also say that player has
            zero power. We call such a player a <term>dummy</term>.          
          </p>
          <p>
            At the other end of this spectrum, if there is some player
            with so much weight that if they say <q>No!</q> to a measure
            then that measure can never pass, we say this player has
            <term>veto power</term> in the system. You may think that
            such a player must have all the power in the system, but 
            this is actually not the case.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="ex-veto">
            <p>
              Consider the weighted voting system <m>[4:3,2,1]</m>.
              Since Player 2 and Player 3 only add to a total weight of 3, 
              this means they cannot pass a measure without Player 1. 
              Thus, Player 1 has veto power. But notice that Player 1 cannot
              pass a measure on their own, because their weight is also
              3, which is less than the quota, <m>q=4</m>. Neither Player 2
              nor Player 3 have veto power. But it also seems they may not
              be a dummies. (We will develop our abilities further to explore
              this question.)
            </p>
          </example>
          <p>
            It turns out that it is possible that more than one player 
            might have veto power within a system:
          </p>
          <example xml:id="ex-veto-multiple">
            <p>
              Consider the weighted voting system <m>[6:4,3,1]</m>. If
              we think about what is required to pass a measure in this 
              system, we see that Player 1 is needed, but so is Player 2.
              Player 1 and Player 3, even if they agree, do not reach
              the total weight required by the quota <m>q=6</m>. Similarly,
              Player 2 and Player 3, even if they agree, do not reach
              the quota. Thus,
              both Player 1 and Player 2 have veto power in this system.
              If either Player 1 or Player 2 say no to a measure, it will
              not pass.
              (It may be the case, now, that Player 3 is indeed a dummy.
              But we need, still, to develop our tools to be able to 
              explore this.)
            </p>
          </example>
          <p>
            In order to systematically explore the Power of No (more
            usually called 
            <q>the Banzhaf power index</q>) we need to introduce the idea
            of a <term>winning coalition</term>. A winning coalition is any
            set of players which can pass a measure; that is, a winning 
            coalition is any set of players whose total weight meets or exceeds
            the quota.
          </p>
          <p>
            The other key idea to introduce is a <term>critical player</term>.
            A critical player in a winning coalition is any player who, if they
            leave the winning coalition, that coalition no longer has enough
            weight to pass a measure and is, thus, no longer a winning coalition.
            It is precisely this fact that leads us to call this way of thinking
            about power as <q>the Power of No</q>, since our method is tallying
            how often it is that a player changing their mind and saying <q>no</q>
            would matter.
          </p>
          <algorithm xml:id="alg-banzhaf">
            <title>How to Compute the Power of No</title>
            <statement>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Write down all winning coalitions in the weighted voting 
                    system. 
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    For each winning coalition, check each player in that coalition
                    to see if they are a critical player. That is, check each player,
                    one at a time, leaving the winning coalition and see if the remaining
                    players form a winning coalition. Note that there may be zero, one, or
                    multiple critical players in a winning coalition.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Determine how many times each player is a critical player. For
                    Player <m>i</m> call this number <m>c_i</m>. Determine,
                    also, the sum of all occurrences of any player being a critical player
                    and call this sum <m>C</m>.
                    That is, find the sum of all the <m>c_i</m>. The notation for this
                    is 
                    <me>
                      \sum_{i=1}^{n} c_i = C
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Each player's <term>Banzhaf power</term> is defined to be the fraction 
                    given by the number of times that player was critical divided by 
                    the total number
                    of times that any player was critical. 
                    That is, the Banzhaf power, 
                    the Power of No, for Player <m>i</m> is defined to be: 
                    <me>
                      B_i=\dfrac{c_i}{C}
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>

            </statement>
          </algorithm>
          <p>
            Note that if we compute the Power of No for each player in this way, 
            the sum of all the powers is 1. Can you see why this is? Can you 
            convince yourself this is true? 
          </p>
          <p>
            It is also worth remembering that instead of 1 we could think of this as 100%,
            and thus we can see that this approach is essentially imagining there to be 
            some total amount of power, thought as 100%, which is then distributed
            amongst the players. Banzhaf power index, then, is one way of describing 
            how that 100% of power is distributed amongst the players. 
          </p>
          <p>
            What is quite interesting is that this is not the only way to think about 
            measuring power in such a system. But before we move on to another method,
            let us work through an example.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="ex-banzhaf-1">
            <p>
              BANZHAF EXAMPLE
            </p>
          </example>
        </section>
        <section xml:id="sec-yes-power">
          <title>The Power of Yes</title>
          <p>
            Suppose we find this focus on no-saying to be too negative. What
            if we were to try to measure how often saying yes might matter? 
            This immediately presents certain conceptual challenges. To motivate
            the approach we will use, it may be useful to imagine the proposal, 
            in the legislative body, of a measure that is very popular with
            the population as a whole. If we imagine all the ways that the
            players within the weighted voting system might raise their hands
            to indicate that they approve this measure, we could focus on 
            precisely when the entire gallery of optimistic and hopeful onlookers
            might erupt into jubilant applause, knowing that, yes, the measure
            will pass. This is the lens that we will use to develop the idea
            of the Power of Yes.
          </p>
          <p>
            As before, we need to define a couple terms. First, rather than 
            building winning coalitions, in this case we imagine all the possible
            orderings of the players. That is, we can imagine all the possible
            orderings of them raising their hands in favor of the measure. 
            We will not consider the possibility of two raising their hands at 
            the same instant. (From what we know of physics and the nature of 
            time this would be impossible anyway.) We will call these possible
            orderings <term>sequential coalitions</term>. Note, though, that
            unlike in the previous case, we do not consider any ordering that
            does not include all the players. There are technical reasons for 
            this, but perhaps we might suggest a psychological-political reason 
            for this as well, that once it becomes clear a measure will pass 
            and also that it is popular, perhaps the remaining players choose
            to also vote in favor of the measure to, so to speak, 
            <q>
              be on the right side of history
            </q>. 
            (We shall note, here, again, that there are plenty of times
            in history that deeply immoral measures have been passed to
            great popular applause.) Within each sequential coalition
            we will be trying to identify the <term>pivotal player</term>, 
            which is the player in the ordered list whose added weight, 
            within the system, moves the measure from <q>not yet approved</q>
            to <q>approved</q>.
          </p>
          <remark>
            <title>A remark on counting:</title>
            <p>
              Though producing a list of all the sequential coalitions can
              be a somewhat arduous task, we can at least say, from the start,
              how many we must produce. This helps us to make sure we
              have not failed to list some ordering
              orderings which would doom our computation of the Power of Yes 
              from the start. (For more on the ideas introduced here, you can
              read <xref ref="sec-counting-techniques"/>.)
            </p>
            <p>
              How many orderings are there of one object? Just one. What
              about orderings of two objects, call them <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>. 
              Well, we can order them <m>AB</m> or <m>BA</m>, correct? 
              What about ordering three objects: A, B, and C?
              <md>
                <mrow>ABC</mrow>
                <mrow>ACB</mrow>
                <mrow>BAC</mrow>
                <mrow>BCA</mrow>
                <mrow>CAB</mrow>
                <mrow>CBA</mrow>
              </md>
              Six possible orderings. 
            </p>
            <p>
              What you might notice in that last example is 
              that we can think of this as a process playing out in 
              stages. How many choices are there for the first object
              in the ordering? Three choices. Now, once you've selected
              the first, how many choices are there for the second
              in line? Only two choices left. Then the remaining object
              must be last in line. This means there are 
              <m>(3)(2)(1)=6</m> orderings. And if there were four objects?
              Then there would be <m>(4)(3)(2)(1)=24</m> orderings.
            </p>
            <p>
              You can see that this swiftly becomes cumbersome to write out,
              and so a notation has been created, factorial notation, which 
              uses the exclamation point, <q>!</q>. So instead of writing 
              <m>(3)(2)(1)</m> we can write <m>3!</m>. And instead of writing
              <m>(4)(3)(2)(1)</m> we can write <m>4!</m>. This is such a
              fundamental idea, and so natural, that as you become more familiar
              with these topics you may find yourself automatically thinking
              of <m>n!</m> as <q>the number of ways to order <m>n</m> objects</q>.
            </p>
            <p>
              It's worth noting, also, that <m>5!=(5)(4)(3)(2)(1)=120</m> and 
              <m>6!=(6)(5)(4)(3)(2)(1)=720</m>. So once we get to analysis of power
              in a weighted voting system with six or more players, we have a 
              rather strenuous task to perform! (There are ways to cleverly save
              ourselves some work, but they require care and practice. For most
              of our analyses in this book, we will keep things on a more reasonable
              scale. There are also online tools available to carry out this sort of 
              power analysis for us. We are working through the details so you can
              intuitively understand <em>how</em> those processes work, not so much
              so that you will drag yourself through onerous and extended power
              calculations by hand.)
            </p>
          </remark>
          <algorithm xml:id="alg-shapley-shubik">
            <title>How to Compute the Power of Yes</title>
            <statement>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Create a list of all the possible orderings of the players
                    within the weighted voting system. These are the sequential
                    coalitions. (Note that this can be a nontrivial task.)
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    For each sequential coalition, determine which player in this
                    ordering is the pivotal player. Note that each sequential
                    coalition will have exactly one pivotal player.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Determine how many times each player is a pivotal player. For
                    Player <m>i</m> call this number <m>s_i</m>. Note that the sum
                    of the <m>s_i</m> should be equal to <m>n!</m> where 
                    <m>n</m> is the number of players. That is, it should always be
                    the case that:
                    <me>
                      \sum_{i=1}^n s_i=n!
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Each player's <term>Shapley-Shubik power</term> is defined to 
                    be the fraction 
                    given by the number of times that player was pivotal divided by 
                    the total number
                    of times that any player was pivotal, which we already know
                    is <m>n!</m>. 
                    That is, the Shapley-Shubik power, 
                    the Power of Yes, for Player <m>i</m> is defined to be: 
                    <me>
                      S_i=\dfrac{s_i}{n!}
                    </me>
                  </p>                
                </li>  
              </ol>
            </statement>
          </algorithm>
        </section>
      </chapter>

