      <chapter xml:id="ch-voting-methods">
        <title>Avoiding Democratic Distortion: Voting Methods</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Much of what we have considered so far can be seen as attempts
            to make things <q>fair</q> or <q>just</q>. We seem to have, as
            humans, many ideas about what is fair or not. We have already
            seen several situations where a design that seems well-suited
            to generate fair or just outcomes has instead exhibited behavior
            that surprised us for its deviation from what seemed fair.
            These ideas of fairness so far have tended to be associated with
            ideas of proportion. We have been pursuing proportionality.
          </p>
          <p>
            In this section, we will examine something different. We will
            concern ourselves with how elections might be best carried out. 
            That is, if we must choose among two or more candidates 
            for some position, 
            or between two or more possible options for solving a problem,
            how should we choose?
          </p>
          <p>
            Many people will immediately arrive at an answer that we should 
            reflect upon. We should have a vote, they say. Surely, this is the 
            very heart of democracy! But <q>democracy</q> is itself a word that
            gathers into it quite a multiplicity of ideas and ideological 
            commitments or assumptions. And, as we have seen before, even if
            we design a system from correct intuitions we must carefully examine
            the behavior of that system to understand whether those intuitions
            about good design do indeed then generate the fair or just or proportional
            behaviors we had envisioned.
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <section xml:id="sec-voting-notation">
          <title>The Will of the Voters</title>
          <p>
            Right away as we think about elections and voting, we are 
            introduced to a sort of abstract idea, which is the 
            <q>will of the voters</q>. (We will set aside, for now, 
            the terribly fraught question of who the voters are, 
            a problem which we might plausibly argue
            has never actually been solved in a truly just way.) 
            But if an election, some collective act of voting, is a 
            process designed to make a decision, should it not also be
            designed for that decision to be most pleasing to the most
            people who voted in that election? For any question, it 
            seems reasonable to imagine some ideal <q>will of the people</q>
            which the method for tallying votes is designed to reveal.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="ex-pizza-vote">
            <title>Choosing Pizza</title>
            <p>
              12 children are choosing what kind of pizza they want
              for a birthday party. (The large pizza from this particular
              pizzeria has 12 pieces.) The options are cheese, pepperoni,
              or olive and onion. Five vote for cheese, four vote for 
              pepperoni, and three vote for olive and onion. So they 
              each get a piece of cheese pizza. Sounds like everything
              worked out as it should.
            </p>
            <p>
              But let us think through this more carefully. What if the
              five who wanted cheese had olive and onion as their 
              second choice? What if the four who wanted pepperoni also
              had olive and onion as their second choice? Does this
              still seem like a good outcome? We now know that seven of
              the 12 children will be eating the pizza that is their
              last choice. On the other hand, if olive and onion had
              been ordered, then everyone would be eating either their
              first or second choice of pizza. It seems that, at least
              from certain points of view and with certain distributions
              of the opinions of voters, our decision to focus only on
              the top choice of ever voter might still lead to outcomes
              that are not in alignment with <q>the will of the people.</q>
            </p>
            <p>
              If you are tempted to object to this, note that another way 
              we might have approached the situation: the children should
              vote on which pizza option should be eliminated first. Clearly
              cheese pizza would have been eliminated, since seven children,
              a majority (which term we will explore in detail later) would 
              have voted to eliminate cheese pizza. (Can you see what pizza
              would then be chosen if this process was repeated with the two
              remaining pizza options?)
            </p>
            <p>
              You might also object, here, and say, well, those are two different
              methods, it should not surprise us, nor even perhaps disturb us,
              that they result in a different outcome. This is a good point! 
              All that this example really does is suggest that perhaps there
              might be some work to be done, mathematically, analytically, to
              think through how we might evaluate the effectiveness and fairness
              of voting methods. There seems to be at least some ambiguity about
              what might best (and thus most fairly?) reflect the will of the 
              people.
            </p>
            <p>
              Finally, though we will work to discern methods for discerning
              the will of the people, we should remember that a decision that 
              accurately reflects the will of the people may not, by that fact, 
              be affirmed as morally good. You will see this sometimes to be 
              assumed in discussions of democracy and voting. But we would do
              well to recall that, at many times in the past, great evil has 
              been affirmed or assented to by democratic processes. Consider
              the American South prior to 1865, the United States
              prior to 1964. Or consider Germany in 1933. At many times, the
              majority has not only incorrect but morally repugnant beliefs
              and practices. We may hope that democracy blunts or minimizes the
              chance of these sorts of outcomes, but we must not be naive.
            </p>
          </example>
          <p>
            In order to clearly think through this analysis, we need to develop 
            some notation. How are we to capture the preferences of some 
            finite collection of voters among some finite list of options,
            whether they be candidates or types of pizza to order? 
          </p>
          <definition xml:id="def-preference-schedule">
            <statement>
              <p>
                A preference schedule for some set of voters collects the 
                number of voters in favor of each possible ordering of the 
                candidates.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </definition>
          <example>
            <title>The Preference Schedule for Pizza Voters</title>
            <p>
              The table below is an example of a preference schedule.
              It completely summarizes the ballots cast by the 12 children
              trying to choose a pizza. At the top of each column is the
              number of ballots of that type. The rows correspond to first-,
              second-, and third-choices on those ballots. We will generally
              include the first column to remind us that this is what 
              these rows mean. Note that the sum of numbers in the first
              row should always correspond to the total number of votes cast.
              In this case, <m>5+4+3=12</m>.
            </p>
            <table>
              <title>12 Children Rank Pizza Type</title>
              <tabular halign="center">
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                  <cell right="medium"> </cell>
                  <cell>5</cell>
                  <cell>4</cell>
                  <cell>3</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell right="medium">1st</cell>
                  <cell>Cheese</cell>
                  <cell>Pepperoni</cell>
                  <cell>Olive and Onion</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell right="medium">2nd</cell>
                  <cell>Olive and Onion</cell>
                  <cell>Olive and Onion</cell>
                  <cell>Pepperoni</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                  <cell right="medium">3rd</cell>
                  <cell>Pepperoni</cell>
                  <cell>Cheese</cell>
                  <cell>Cheese</cell>
                </row>
              </tabular>
            </table>
          </example>
          <p>
            Such a table can be easily extended to as many rows as necessary.
            It is good to think about how many columns might be needed, though.
            With three candidates, we would never need more than six columns.
            Can you see why? It depends on the number of possible orderings 
            of three candidates. If there were four candidates, the number of
            possible orderings of candidates rises to 24. With five candidates
            we might have 120 possible kinds of ballots cast. In all these 
            cases we can still carry out the analyses that we will develop 
            below. But you can see that the space of possible outcomes rises
            quite rapidly. (This is called the combinatorial explosion, and we 
            will speak more about it in later sections.)
          </p>
        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-bad-voting">
          <title>What Can Go Wrong?</title>
          <p>
            In <xref ref="ex-pizza-vote"/> we may have already begun to suspect
            that we will need to be quite careful about how we think about what
            the behavior of a voting method should be. The usual approach to this
            question is to declare our ideas of fairness in an election. There
            are many such <q>fairness criteria</q> that are suggested and 
            studied. We will focus our attention on four of them.
          </p>
          <p>
            MAJORITY
          </p>
        </section>
        <section xml:id="sec-fairness-criteria">
          <title>Four Ideas of Fairness</title>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              We will now declare, as carefully as possible, our ideas
              about what should happen in a voting method that is fair.
              By naming these ideas of fairness, we will be defining
              parameters for us to use in judging existing or future
              methods of voting. The process of determining whether a
              method of voting will always satisfy some criterion can 
              be a rigorous task.
            </p>
            <p>
              Of the four ideas of fairness that we will here propose, 
              two may be thought of as <term>static</term>, resting
              only on the fixed preferences of the voters and a fixed list
              of candidates. The other two ideas of fairness may be thought 
              of as <term>dynamic</term>, where either the preferences of the 
              voters or the participation of candidates might change in 
              particular ways.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-static-fairness">
            <title>Static Fairness Criteria</title>
            <p>
              <definition xml:id="def-majority">
                <title>Majority Fairness Criterion</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    In an election, if some candidate has the majority of first-place
                    votes, then this candidate should win.
                  </p>
                </statement>
              </definition>  
              <definition xml:id="def-condorcet">
                <title>The Condorcet Fairness Criterion</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    In an election, if some candidate would win all head-to-head
                    matchups with other candidates, then that candidate should win
                    the election.
                  </p>
                </statement>
              </definition>
            </p>
          </subsection>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-dynamic-fairness">
            <title>Dynamic Fairness Criteria</title>
            <p> 

            </p>             
            <definition xml:id="def-iia">
              <title>Independence of Irrelevant Alternatives Fairness Criterion</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  In an election, if some candidate would win and some other non-winning
                  candidate drops out of the election, then the original winning candidate
                  should still win the election.
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            <definition xml:id="def-monotonicity">
              <title>The Monotonicity Fairness Criterion</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  In an election, if some candidate would win and a subset of 
                  voters change their ballots only by moving that candidate higher
                  on their ballots, then that candidate should still win. 
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
          </subsection>
        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-voting-methods">
          <title>Four Voting Methods</title>
          <introduction> 
            <p>
              With the the ideas of fairness defined by the four Fairness
              Criteria above, let us now explore some methods of determining
              a winner in an election, once we have been provided with a 
              preference schedule summarizing voter opinion on the candidates.
            </p>
            <p>
              Two other things to keep in mind: first, that none of the following
              analysis is needed if there are only two candidates. 
              When there are only two candidates, the problems we are seeking
              to solve do not arise. (But notice that preventing more than two
              candidates from pursuing office might indeed be anti-democratic. 
              We should not assume that we may easily avoid complexity or paradox
              by ruling out, in advance, full participation of all those who would
              like to seek to serve in office.)
              Second, though
              we will consider situations where each ballot provides a complete
              ranking of all the candidates, there are simple ways to adapt the
              results we will find to account for ballots with incomplete information.
              That is, an objection that not all voters would fill out their ballot
              completely and therefore no alternative methods should be considered
              is an invalid objection. (It is somewhat common to hear objections to
              alternative methods of voting, usually relying upon claims about the 
              ignorance or laziness of voters. Ignorance and laziness in voting, when
              they occur, are, in the opinion of this author, likely to be the effect
              of poor voting methods and legislative and executive leaders who fail
              to address the real-world material needs of voters.)
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-plurality">
            <title>The Plurality Method</title>
            <p>
              The Plurality Method likely needs little introduction. It
              is the most familiar method to most people who have lived
              within democratic processes. It is very simple to set up, 
              explain, and determining a winner is also quite straightforward.
            </p>
            <p>
              Unfortunately, as we will see, it is quite prone to some
              rather serious problems. If you remember nothing else from all 
              that follows, please remember this: the Plurality Method, despite
              its ease of use, should be replaced by other methods if the goal
              is to avoid rather serious negative behaviors. We will
              see why this is so.
            </p>
            <algorithm xml:id="alg-plurality-method">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Whichever candidate has received the most
                        first-place votes is declared the winner.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        If there is a tie between two or more candidates with
                        the most first-place votes, the tie should be broken
                        using a predetermined tiebreak method. (This could be
                        to declare the winner is the one 
                        with the most second-place votes (and if that is also a
                        tie using the third-place votes to break the tie, etc.), or
                        could be determined by using one of the other 
                        voting methods.)
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </algorithm>
            <p>
              You can see that this is indeed a very simple method. In
              fact, voters need not even think about who their second or
              third or lower choices might be. In the USA this sort of 
              indifference to lower choices has become so ingrained
              as to feel almost natural. But even if your favorite candy
              is a Theo chocolate bar, surely it matters whether your
              second choice is Necco Wafers or Skittles? Most of us
              have gradations of preference for most things, and perhaps
              it behooves us to be informed enough to learn these 
              preferences when it comes to organizing our preferences and
              practices around who gets food, housing, and whether we
              should engage in war or support the starvation of children
              in the name of freedom and justice and democracy.
            </p>
            <p>
              But we can be more specific about the failures of the
              Plurality Method. First, notice that 
              <xref ref="ex-pizza-vote"/> is in fact an example of a
              bad behavior by the Plurality Method. In that case, 
              pepperoni won the vote even though most of the children
              had pepperoni as their least favorite choice!
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-plurality-bad">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  MORE HERE
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  MORE HERE
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  MORE HERE
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
          </subsection>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-instant-runoff">
            <title>Instant Runoff Voting Method</title>
            <p>
              The most commonly used alternative, in political
              situations, is Instant Runoff Voting, also sometimes 
              called Ranked Choice Voting. 
            </p>
          </subsection>

        </section>
        <section xml:id="sec-methods-and-fairness">
          <title>The Satisfaction of Fairness Criteria by Voting Methods</title>
          <p>
            We have already seen some examples of voting methods 
            satisfying or failing to satisfy Fairness Criteria. We will 
            summarize those results here:
          </p>
          <p>
            SUMMARY OF PREVIOUS RESULTS. Plurality violates Condorcet. Etc.
          </p>
        </section>
      </chapter>

