      <chapter xml:id="ch-gerrymandering">
        <title>Distortion of Representation: Gerrymandering</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            In our personal relationships, it is important to establish
            boundaries. In the political or legal realm the ability to 
            establish boundaries is a great power. Our ideas of fairness 
            might also have something to say here. As in so many situations
            we have already examined, we will once again be leaning on 
            our intuition about proportionality to see if we can identify
            outcomes that seem troubling or even unfair or unjust.
          </p>
          <p>
            This text is being written from within the United States of America. 
            This has driven many of the previous discussions and their examples. 
            In this chapter, to avoid too much emotional interaction with the 
            party particulars of the USA, the idea of political gerrymandering will
            be explored using two imaginary parties: the Purple Party and the 
            Orange party. Of course, what this means is we are still operating within
            an imagined situation where there are two major parties. Many countries
            have more than two major parties. Obviously, in such a case there will
            be even more complex dynamics. As we explore the ways that the establishment
            of boundaries may distort representation in a two-party situation, 
            keep in mind what might or might not carry over to the multi-party case.
            We should also state outright that none of our analysis and attention
            should be taken as any sort of endorsement of the two-party approach. 
            (We might want to allow for the case, though, that our analysis might
            lead us to the opposite of an endorsement of such a system. Perhaps.)
          </p>
        </introduction>
        <section xml:id="sec-gerry-motivation">
          <title>What Would Distortion Look like?</title>
          <p>
            What could go wrong? As so often, we will begin with an example. To keep
            things easier to contemplate, let us assume that the entire population
            is eligible to vote and does vote in every election. 
            Let us further assume that all are 
            registered as either Purple Party or Orange Party, and that they are quite
            loyal to their parties. (If you are thinking that this is a strong set
            of assumptions, you are correct. Reflect a bit on whether, even so, the
            insights we might gain would still apply to the more complex real-world
            situation in the USA circa 2025.)
          </p>
          <example>
            <title>Purple Favoring Itself</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The state of Omoo has 120,054 people in it, and thus
                should be represented in the nation's 
                proportional-representation legislature by four representatives.
                The state government is currently controlled by the Purple Party, 
                which has the responsibility, now, to draw the borders for the
                legislative districts which will be represented in the national
                legislature. 
              </p>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      If the population is made up of 61,043 Purple voters and 
                      59,011 Orange voters, what would be the most fair way for 
                      this state to be represented in the national legislature?
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Is it possible that the boundaries be drawn so that the
                      Purple Party gets three or even all four representatives?
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Most fair would be two representatives for each party.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      Yes, the Purple Party could have between 1 and 4 
                      representatives in the legislature. The Orange Party 
                      could have between 0 and 3 representatives. 
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      This is very similar to problems we have solved in earlier
                      chapters. Since the Purple Party has 50.8% of the population
                      and the Orange Party has 49.2% of the population, a 50% to 
                      50% split of the representatives seems more fair than a 75%
                      to 25% (or 100% to 0%) split.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      We will explore visual expressions of this idea later,
                      but aiming at roughly equal populations in each district (which
                      is how the USA system works) and depending on the actual spatial
                      distribution of the Purple and Orange voters, it is be possible that the
                      Purple Party wins all four districts each by a narrow margin. 
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </example>
          <p>
            Now, you might respond, <q>So what?</q> There are close election
            results all the time! Why should we worry if Purple manages four
            close wins? True. And this is precisely what makes analysis of this
            sort of question quite challenging and tricky. How can we get a handle
            on when something is simply a result of random processes and the messy
            churn of human thought and action? Should we always just assume that
            things are essentially unbiased and safe? Or would it be more prudent
            to develop the tools and habits of investigation and reflection?
          </p>
          <p>
            We should not minimize, though, the challenge here. As we move into 
            the analysis of ever more complex systems, we also enter into situations
            where outcomes can be explained by a variety of factors, some of which
            are simply randomness and chance, others of which might be orchestrated
            by other humans or processes. This also means we may need to be more 
            sophisticated in how we reflect and investigate. For example, in the 
            situation described above, if the Purple Party won all four seats, each
            one by a narrow margin, after
            drawing the boundaries, we might want to find a way to look at the 
            map of the legislative districts themselves to help us decide whether 
            the districts made a certain natural sort of sense. How might we 
            recognize a map of district boundaries that didn't seem to <q>make sense</q>?
            What kind of tools would we have to develop to even speak coherently on 
            such a question?
          </p>
        </section>
        <section xml:id="sec-gerry-wasted">
          <title>One View on Distortion: Wasted Votes</title>
          <p>
            One approach to analysis of possible gerrymandering is to 
            investigate the idea of <term>wasted votes</term>. Though this
            term is expressive and easy to remember, it does seem to carry
            some negative connotation with it in the word <q>wasted</q>. 
            We can imagine a booster of democratic processes objecting to
            the word, some sort of naively hopeful 
            <q>no vote is every truly wasted</q> sentiment. It is pretty
            to hope so. It is also worth noting that the vague notion 
            of wasting a vote seems more likely to arise in precisely the
            sort of two-party system dominant in the USA, especially in
            those localities that still run their elections using the 
            Plurality Method discussed in 
            <xref ref="sec-voting-methods"/>. The idea of a 
            <q>wasted vote</q> loses coherent meaning in an election
            using the Instant Runoff Voting Method, or the 
            Borda Count Voting Method,  or the Pairwise Comparisons 
            Voting Method. Indeed, this seems one of the major
            commendable aspects of these methods in contradistinction 
            to the Plurality Voting Method. 
          </p>
        </section>
        <section xml:id="sec-gerry-howto">
          <title>Distorting on Purpose: How to Gerrymander</title>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              Though the concept of wasted votes 
              and the Efficiency Gap measure derived from them can
              be powerful tools
              for motivating our exploration of how a system might fail
              to reflect the preference of a significant portion of voters,
              they have some limitations. For one, there will always be some
              votes that are not reflected in the results. That is the 
              nature of holding an election.
            </p>
            <p>
              The frequent absurdity of discourse around these topics 
              was brought into rather sharp focus in August 2025, when 
              a Republican, not content with the currently right-
              distorted state of the USA, complained 
              on a eugenics-inclined-billionaire-owned 
              social media site about the fact 
              that eight states have no Republican representation in
              the House of Representatives. Included in the list was 
              the apparently outrageous case of Vermont, which has 32% 
              of voters that vote Republican yet have zero Republicans
              in the House. Of course, Vermont has such a small population
              that it is apportioned only a single representative in 
              the House. Was the tweeter arguing that 32% should be 
              enough to claim that entire single representative for  
              the Republicans?
            </p>
            <p>
              The tool does require critical thinking, though.
              There are some subtleties to consider, though. It 
              is perhaps best to think of the Efficiency Gap defined 
              in the previous section as an alert that calls for more
              careful analysis of the boundaries drawn for
              the districts. 
            </p>
            <p>
              As a simple example: in the USA there has been a series
              of demographic movements called the <q>Great Sort</q>, which
              essentially reflects people moving to places that they perceive
              to have a population whose political beliefs and/or values are
              more well aligned to their own. The person who chooses to move
              to rural Idaho and the person who chooses to move to the Capitol
              Hill neighborhood in Seattle will tend to have distinctly dissimilar
              political inclinations. (We are speaking only in tendencies and 
              generalities here, of course. Rather, we should say we are speaking
              of probabilities, about which we will speak at much greater length
              later.)
            </p>
            <p>
              The point, then, is that it would be good to be able to recognize,
              in the event of what seems to be possible irregularities, whether
              this has come to be from a sort of natural variation or rather
              has been engineered by those in control of drawing the boundaries.
              This sort of manipulation of boundaries to distort outcomes is 
              precisely the behavior that is meant by the word 
              <term>gerrymandering</term>.
            </p>
            <p>
              As is so often the case, an extremely effective 
              way to improve our ability
              to recognize when a system is being manipulated is
              to attempt to understand how we ourselves might 
              manipulate it, given the chance.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-gerrypacking">
            <title>How to Pack</title>
            <p>
              Suppose you are a member of the Purple Party. Your 
              state has a significant number of Orange voters, maybe
              even more Orange voters than Purple, but you
              would like to make sure the Purple Party is able to 
              achieve more representation than would match the proportion
              of Purple Party voters. 
            </p>
            <p>
              Keeping in mind that the Efficiency Gap would reflect the
              distortion we are trying to achieve, perhaps we should think
              about how to make sure a lot of Orange Party votes are wasted.
            </p>
            <p>
              KEEP GOING WITH PACKING
            </p>
          </subsection>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-gerrycracking">
            <title>How to Crack</title>
            <p>
              For the next strategy, let us consider the situation
              where we are an Orange Party official tasked with 
              drawing the boundaries of the legislative districts
              in our state. The Orange Party has more voters in this
              state, and yet we would like to make sure that the 
              representation is disproportionately Orange. How might
              we go about doing this?
            </p>
            <p>
              KEEP GOING WITH CRACKING.
            </p>
          </subsection>
        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-gerry-analysis">
          <title>Another View on Distortion: Naturality</title>
          <p>
            1) HOW COULD WE DECIDE WHETHER SOMETHING WRONG HAS BEEN DONE?
            2) OTHER EXPLANATION: BIRDS OF A FEATHER / GREAT SORT.
            3) SHAPE OF DISTRICT -- NATURAL OR NOT?
            4) HISTORY / CULTURE: BUT HOW IS THAT ENTANGLED WITH OLD BIASES?
            5) REDLINING
            6) TWO PARTIES AGAIN: AN ASSUMPTION THAT ONE MUST IDENTIFY WITH ONE
            OR THE OTHER. LIMITED RANGE OF IDEAS. BASELINE ASSUMPTIONS THAT ARE
            FORCED ON EVERYONE.
          </p>
        </section>
      </chapter>

