      <chapter xml:id="ch-financial-math">
        <title>Financial Mathematics</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            You are enmeshed in a system that insists upon your compliance
            in order for you to continue to eat. Only willing subjects to
            this system are afforded the calories and nutrients that
            allow their physical and biological substrate to continue to 
            function. If this sounds coercive, you are correct. It is.
          </p>
          <p>
            One of the key implements of coercion and power in the 
            current world system is the monetary system and its associated
            practices of credit and debt. This financial system is 
            massively complex at this point, including huge portions that
            not only run on computers but are controlled by computers, 
            sometimes in ways few humans do <em>or even can</em> 
            understand. The basics of interest, debt, credit, and the time 
            value of money will be covered in this chapter, with the 
            intention that the careful learners emerge better able to 
            protect themselves from those with massive power within
            the system. That is, the very rich and the institutions they
            control.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will begin by introducing the concept of 
            <term>interest</term>, which is nothing more complex
            than a periodic proportional increase in an amount
            of money. Yet in practice what it becomes is a
            fee charged by those with more than enough
            money to live to those with less than enough money
            to live... to live.
          </p>
          <p>
            We will discuss this further once we have established
            the mechanics of the system. But keep this in mind as well:
            as we explore the logic and movement in this system, 
            remember always that it is a human system, contingent,
            changeable. Humanity has arranged its behavior and care
            for each other radically differently for the vast majority
            of human history. 
            <em>
              Economics and finance are often taught and thought as
              if the patterns and practices are as natural and eternal
              as the laws of nature. They are not, and should not be
              thought of that way.
            </em>
          </p>
          <remark>
            <p>
              The world has been and will be other than it now is.
              View with suspicion those who, comfortable atop a
              heap of the miserable, insist the world can never
              be otherwise.
            </p>
          </remark>
        </introduction>
        <section xml:id="sec-interest">
          <title>Interest and Time</title>
          <p>
            We will take the idea of money as given, though, again, 
            one must keep in mind that it is only a contingent set
            of human practices that allow it to so thoroughly organize
            our lives.
          </p>
          <p>
            Once money is posited as part of the system, as a sort of 
            universal unit of exchange that can provide access to
            goods and services, necessary and frivolous alike, the issue
            of time also presents itself. Specifically, how does (or 
            should?) time and money interact. One way is that you do 
            or will eventually trade away part of your life to your
            boss, a portion of each of your finite number of days, in 
            exchange for money. This money can, in theory, then be 
            used to provide food and shelter and medical care to you
            and those you love.
          </p>
          <p>
            Throughout this book, we have often found ourselves in 
            pursuit of equivalents. (Or <q>equivalence</q>.) Here we find
            another needed pursuit: suppose you need money right now and 
            someone else has that money. Further, that person does not 
            need the money they have for use right now. They could give
            the money to you for you to use for the needed food or housing
            or medical care. They might ask only for the same amount of money
            in return at some future (specified or unspecified) date. 
            This rarely occurs. Generally, a larger amount of future money is
            expected in return.
          </p>
          <p>
            There are a variety of reasons that might be given for this
            expectation. We might even view some of them as, more or 
            less, reasonable. What we must never do is lose sight of the
            fact that any such reason runs the risk of becoming so encrusted,
            even completely obscured by habit and privilege, that it
            becomes an item of faith upon which the lives and well-being of
            vulnerable people will be sacrificed without hesitation. 
          </p>
          <p>
            So let us present the reasons that the future repayment might
            be expected to be larger than the original loan amount, wary and
            with full awareness of the ways
            these reasons can be used to justify privation, want, 
            and exploitation of vulnerable persons. 
          </p>
          <p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Risk: the borrower may not pay the agreed future
                  amount, either because they will not or cannot. Thus, 
                  the creditor should be compensated for taking this risk
                  and the amount repaid should be larger than that loaned.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Lost access to the loaned money: the creditor no 
                  longer has the use of the loaned money in the interval
                  between loaning it and being repaid. Thus, the creditor 
                  should be compensated for this decrease in their 
                  financial autonomy 
                  and the amount repaid should be larger than that loaned.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Inflation: historically, on average, the value of 
                  money has a tendency to decrease. This means a dollar now
                  tends to be able to purchase more than a dollar in a
                  month or a year or a decade. (when I was a teen, it cost
                  $7 to see an evening movie. Nowadays, a teen would watch
                  it free via torrent on their phone. But if they went to the
                  theater to see an evening movie it would cost around $15.) 
                  Since a dollar now will (usually) buy less than a dollar in 
                  the future, the creditor should be compensated to mitigate 
                  this decay in purchasing power
                  and the amount repaid should be larger than that loaned.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>

          <example xml:id="ex-time-interest">
            <title>Interest: Borrowing and Repaying</title>              
            <p>
              Mary needs $100 to buy food for her four children. 
              Richard has $100 he is not using and will not need for a 
              month. He agrees to loan Mary money to feed her 
              children as long as she will pay him back an extra 
              10% at the end of the month. Mary has little choice 
              but to agree.
            </p>
            <p>
              How much does Mary pay at the end of the month? We
              know from what we learned in 
              <xref ref="ch-percent-proportion"/>
              that 10% of $100 is: 
              <me>
                (0.10)(100)=10
              </me>
              So Mary will repay the original $100 plus the 
              extra $10 for a total of $110. We call the
              $10 the <term>interest</term>. We call the 10% 
              the <term>interest rate</term> for the period of
              one month.
            </p>
          </example>

          <subsection xml:id="subsec-simple-interest">
            <title>Simple Interest</title>
            <p>
              Suppose you were to put money into a savings account at
              some financial institution. You should think of this as
              you giving a loan to this institution. We are often trained
              or expected to think of this as the institution doing us the
              favor of protecting our money. It is true that a bank tends
              to be more difficult to rob than a person with cash. But the 
              more important aspect of this exchange is that you are granting
              the institution the use of that money for some period of time
              until you take it out of the institution again. Thus, according 
              to the logic described above, the institution should pay you
              some interest for the use of this money. (We will later 
              discuss what benefit this has for the institution and what 
              <q>use</q> might mean in this context.)
            </p>
            <p>
              Suppose you place $1000 into this institution, which agrees
              to pay you a 1% interest payment on this amount for each
              month that you leave it in the bank. This interest payment
              would thus be:
              <me>
                (0.01)(1000)=10
              </me> 
              That is, the bank would pay you $10 at the end of the first
              month. If you left the $1000 in the bank for another month, 
              you would be given another $10 payment by the bank. And so
              on.
            </p>
            <p>
              This approach to the practice is called <term>simple interest</term>
              and we would say you were earning monthly 1% simple interest. We can 
              even form a simple formula to summarize this situation. If you 
              deposit some amount <m>P_0</m> earning a per time period simple interest
              rate of <m>r</m> for <m>n</m> of these time periods, how much money, <m>P</m>,
              would you now be entitled to withdraw from the bank?
            </p>
            <p>
              You would be entitled to:
              <men>
                P=P_0+(n)(r)(P_0)=P_0+nrP_0=P_0(1+nr)
              </men>
              This is worth thinking through. But it should not be too confusing.
              Each time period that passes, the bank must give us a new amount based
              on a percentage of the <em>original</em> deposit, which is <m>P_0</m>.
              That amount is the same every time, <m>r \times P_0</m>. So if it has 
              been paid <m>n</m> times? Then <m>n \times r \times P_0</m> has been 
              added to the original amount of <m>P_0</m>. The other forms are all
              merely algebraic adjustments.
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-simple-interest">
              <title>An Example of Simple Interest</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Marty places $600 into a bank which will pay them 4% simple
                  interest every two months. How much money can Marty take out
                  of this account if they leave it in the bank for eight months?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  <me>
                    P=600(1+(0.04)(4))=696
                  </me>
                  That is, $696.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  In one sense, we are simply plugging in the appropriate values
                  of the variables. Since $600 is deposited, this means that 
                  <m>P_0=600</m>. Since the simple interest rate for every two months
                  is 4%, we have <m>r=0.04</m>. We must be slightly careful with the 
                  eight months, but if the money is in the bank for eight months and 
                  the period for paying interest is two months then because 
                  <m>\frac{8}{2}=4</m> we know that the interest will be paid four 
                  times. That is, <m>n=4</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  We can also think it through chronologically, to help us develop
                  our intuition about money and its relationship to time in such
                  situations as this. With simple interest, the interest payment is
                  the same every time so we can simply compute what that payment is.
                  In this case, 4% of $600 is <m>(0.04)(600)=24</m>. So every two 
                  months, Marty gets $24 added to their account. This happens four 
                  times: after two months, after four months, after six months, 
                  and after eight months. So the total will be:
                  <me>
                    600+24+24+24+24=600+(4)(24)=600+96=696
                  </me>
                  All the formula has done is to somewhat automate this thinking
                  for us. It may not matter much in a case like this with only a
                  few interest payments, but if we were considering hourly interest
                  payments that were adding up over the course of decades, we might
                  be rather grateful to relinquish the payment-by-payment viewpoint.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              This all seems quite simple, and is. (It is called 
              <q>simple interest</q> after all.) Yet there remains a fine point
              we should notice. If, as we have described, the money is not removed
              from the bank, we have a strange situation. At the start, the bank
              was paying a percentage of the money placed there. But as time
              goes along that amount sitting in the bank has grown. Yet the bank
              keeps paying the same fixed payment, based only on the original amount 
              rather than the new larger amount that the customer could withdraw
              if they chose. We will leave aside the tricky question of what
              exactly is going on here. (Where did this money come from? Did a new
              stack of bills burst into existence somewhere deep in the bank's 
              vaults?) Let us just notice that the customer is now allowing the 
              bank access to more money than at the start. Yet the bank is still
              only paying that original amount of interest? The technical term 
              (beyond the scope of this course and text) for discussing this
              aspect of the behavior of the system is 
              <term>force of interest</term>. We would say that in the context
              described, there is a declining force of interest, which benefits
              the borrower (in this case the bank) and is not in favor of the 
              creditor (in this case the customer).
            </p>
            <p>
              The more common practice, then, for computing interest is the form
              that keeps the force of interest constant. That practice is called
              <term>compound interest</term>.
            </p>
          </subsection>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-compound-interest">
            <title>Compound Interest</title>
            <p>
              We should use caution when discussing a situation
              involving two parties and in which one party has more 
              money than it 
              needs and the other party has less money than it needs. Still
              there is an idea of fairness lurking here, which is that
              if the amount of money the bank is holding has increased
              then the bank should be paying a larger amount of interest
              in return for control of that larger amount of money.
            </p>
            <p>
              You might already have an intuition about this. All that needs to
              be done is to change the starting point. The problem with the
              simple interest situation is that it is always looking back to
              the original amount of money. What should happen instead? The
              interest should be computed based on the current amount of money
              in the account! We just need to be updating our perspective.
            </p>
            <remark>
              <p>
                We might also conceptualize this as taking the money out and 
                re-depositing it at each period, thus updating the <m>P_0</m>
                in the simple interest formula each time. This is also another
                way to see how compound interest has a certain logic to it:
                why should the creditor have to show up, withdraw and then 
                re-deposit the money to avoid getting a lower and lower 
                monetary benefit? Rather, the process should update itself.
                This is what compound interest does.
              </p>
            </remark>
            <p>
              As before, there is a formula we might use. We present it
              in a few different forms to allow for different angles on
              understanding it intuitively. In this formula, <m>P_0</m> is 
              the initial amount deposited (or, equivalently, loaned), 
              <m>r</m> is the 
              per-period interest rate (the percent increase each time period),
              and <m>t</m> is the number of time periods that the money is
              left in the account (or, equivalently, no payments are made
              by the borrower).
              <men xml:id="eqn-compound-interest">
                P=P_0(1+r)^t
              </men>
              If we look at this formula, remember that an exponent is
              just instructing us to repeatedly multiply by some factor.
            </p>
            <p>
              This is easily demonstrated with an example. We will keep most
              details the same as before, only switching to compound interest 
              instead of simple interest.
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-compound-interest">
              <title>An Example of Compound Interest</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Marty places $600 into a bank which will pay them 4% compound
                  interest every two months. How much money can Marty take out
                  of this account if they leave it in the bank for eight months?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  $701.92
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  One way to think about this is step-by-step. The interest will
                  be paid four times.
                  <ol>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        After two months, the new amount in the account is:
                        <me>
                          600 + 600(0.04)=600(1+0.04)=600+24=624
                        </me>
                        Notice that after one time period, the result is the
                        same as for simple interest, $624. This should have 
                        been your expectation!
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Four months into the process, the interest is paid again, 
                        but now on the <em>new</em> amount:
                        <me>
                          624+624(0.04)=624(1+0.04)
                        </me>
                        <me>
                          =624+24.96=648.96
                        </me>
                        This is not a very large change, but you can see that this
                        amount is different, slightly more, than what would be in
                        the account under simple interest.
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        We can repeat this twice more for the six-month mark:
                        <me>
                          648.96+(648.96)(0.04)=648.96(1+0.04)
                        </me>
                        <me>
                          =648.96+25.9584=674.9184
                        </me>
                        And for the eight-month mark:
                        <me>
                          674.9184+(674.9184)(0.04)=674.9184(1+0.04)
                        </me>
                        <me>
                          =701.915136
                        </me>
                        Now you may notice a strange thing here: fractions of a cent.
                        If you were the bank customer and were to look at your 
                        account information at these times, you would see an amount
                        rounded to the nearest cent. This gives our final answer:
                        $701.92
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ol>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              The intermediate steps in the solution given above are written 
              in a variety of ways precisely to give you intuition about the
              formula. Notice that at each stage, the previous amount of money
              is being multiplied by the factor <m>(1+0.04)=1.04</m>. This is
              precisely the number that increases the amount by 4% each time!
              This, in turn, explains the exponent and why that exponent should
              be 4. The interest was paid four times. The amount in the account
              was increased by 4% four times. Thus:
              <me>
                600(1+0.04)^4=600(1.04)^4=701.92
              </me>
              But see how much more compact that is than to step through the 
              process one interest-period at a time? In this example we can
              do it either way and it is not terribly different in effort,
              but what if we wanted to know how much money there would be
              in the account after 80 months? Or 120 months? 
              In each of those cases
              it would be frustrating and boring to go step by step through
              the process, yet to type in the formula <m>600(1.04)^{40}</m> or 
              <m>600(1.04)^{60}</m> is essentially the same amount of work
              as for the case of eight months.
            </p>
            <p>
              A relatively simple idea! But of course, nothing can be left
              quite so simple, especially not by bankers. This is the perfect 
              place for a great quote from the play by Bertolt Brecht, 
              <pubtitle>The Threepenny Opera</pubtitle>:
              <q>
                What is the robbing of a bank
                compared to the founding of a bank?
              </q>
            </p>
          </subsection>

          <subsection xml:id="subsec-apr-compound">
            <title>APR and Compound Interest</title>
            <p>
              What you will most often see, when interest rates are being
              reported for an account or loan, is an <q>APR</q>, which 
              stands for <term>annual percentage rate</term>. This number
              is tricky and often has a huge amount of fine print associated
              with it. Setting aside those considerations, we will focus on 
              understanding its use in practical  
              situations. The key to all of this is to understand that,
              despite the words that make up the name for this concept,
              <em>
                it does not tell you the annual percentage increase
                in the account if you left alone it for a year.
              </em>
            </p>
            <p>
              So, how to understand APR? The good news is that we need only
              make a small adjustment to the compound interest formula 
              above. Where that introduction
              of compound interest focused on the percent change over
              each period of interest payment, the APR imagines
              dividing that percentage by however many times per year
              that the interest is being paid.
            </p>
            <p>
              To be explicit: if a savings account is paying 4% APR 
              compounded monthly, then the per month interest rate is
              <m>\frac{0.04}{12}</m>. Any time we are talking about
              an actual percent change in the amount for some time
              period, we call that the <term>effective interest rate</term>
              for that time period. So a 4% APR compounded monthly (also 
              sometimes described as a 4% monthly APR or a 4% APR paid
              monthly) means that the monthly effective interest rate
              is that 4% divided by 12. We think of that 4% as being 
              divided by the number of times that interest is paid
              in that year. (Thus for a daily APR of 4% the effective 
              interest rate each day would be <m>\frac{0.04}{365}</m>.)
            </p>
            <p>
              But this all means we have to make not one but two adjustments
              to the compound interest formula. One adjustment is to the
              percent change piece: no longer will it be just the <q>rate</q>, 
              now it will be the APR (in decimal form) divided by the number
              of times per year that interest is paid. The second adjustment is
              to the exponent. Where in the previous version of the formula, we 
              defined <m>t</m> to be the number of periods for which interest
              was paid, that is, the number of compounding periods, we will
              now switch to thinking of <m>t</m> always being measured in years.
              Think of this as a shift called for by our switch to the APR
              viewpoint. (Remember, that <q>A</q> in APR stands for 
              <q>annual</q>.)
            </p>
            <p>
              So the new formula for compound interest will be as follows:
              If the APR is <m>r</m> 
              compounded <m>n</m> times per year for <m>t</m> years, and the
              initial amount invested is <m>P_0</m>, then the amount in the
              account after those <m>t</m> years will be:
              <men xml:id="eqn-apr-compound">
                P=P_0\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^{nt}
              </men>
               As always, let us pause a moment to try to fill in the intuition
               about this formula. Why does it do what we claim it does? Remember
               that what we are trying to do is to allow the percent increase to
               be applied as many times as makes sense. If the interest amount
               is added <m>n</m> times per year and the money is left in the
               account for <m>t</m> years, then interest will be paid <m>nt</m>
               times. That means that whatever percent increase, per period,
               we want to apply must be applied <m>nt</m> times, and that is 
               precisely what the exponent accomplishes. As for that percent
               increase: each of the <m>n</m> times per year it is paid, that 
               percent is the APR <m>r</m>, in its decimal form, divided by
               the number of times per year the interest is paid. So the 
               owner of the account receives <m>\frac{r}{n}</m> interest 
               increases <m>n</m> times each year. So the factor to increase 
               that original deposit of <m>P_0</m> is the usual 
               <m>\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)</m>. 
               The exponent on this factor repeats the
               interest payments for the proper number of times.
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-apr-compound-1">
              <title>An Example of Compound Interest with APR</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Gilberte would like to save some money to purchase
                  a proper memorial stone for her lover, killed in
                  the war. She has $500 and has found a bank that
                  offers a savings account that pays an APR of
                  3% compounded monthly. If she makes this deposit and 
                  leaves the money in the bank for two years, how much 
                  money does she have?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  $530.88
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  In a situation like this, we can lean on the formula.
                  The only trick is to make sure we have interpreted the
                  details of the problem correctly and translated those 
                  details into the proper values for each variable.
                  In this case:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        The amount deposited is not determined any differently
                        from previous interest formulas: since Gilberte
                        is depositing $500 we know that <m>P_0=500</m>. 
                        So far we have:
                        <me>
                          P=500\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^{nt}
                        </me>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        The APR is 3% compounded monthly. This gives us 
                        two pieces of information. First, the rate <m>r=0.03</m>. 
                        Equally important, the monthly compounding tells us
                        that the interest will be paid 12 times per year, so
                        <m>n=12</m>. Thus we now have:
                        <me>
                          P=500\left(1+\frac{0.03}{12}\right)^{12t}
                        </me>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <p>
                        Finally, we are told that Gilberte plans to leave
                        the money in the savings account for two years
                        without any additional deposits or withdrawals.
                        That means that the final variable, representing
                        time in years, should be <m>t=2</m>. Thus:
                        <me>
                          P=500\left(1+\frac{0.03}{12}\right)^{(12)(2)}=530.88
                        </me>
                      </p>
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              Before we move on, we should note one other fact about this 
              situation. Once the APR, compounding period, and initial 
              deposit have been set, the only variable that affects the balance 
              in the savings account is time, <m>t</m>. That means we could,
              as in <xref ref="ch-preliminaries"/>, define the current
              amount in the account as a function of that one variable. That is, 
              if, as in the example, we know that <m>P_0=500, r=0.03, n=12</m> 
              then we may write the function:
              <me>
                P=500\left(1+\frac{0.03}{12}\right)^{12t}=500(1.0025)^{12t}
              </me>
              <me>
                =500(1.0304159569135067)^t
              </me>
              The only thing we should be very careful about in such a situation is that 
              we should technically only trust this formula for values of <m>t</m> that
              (in this case) correspond to <m>\frac{1}{n}=\frac{1}{12}</m> of a year.
              That is: since this formula is designed to represent money in the account
              just after an interest payment has been added to the amount in the account,
              we should only use the formula for values of <m>t</m> that correspond to
              those sorts of moments. An easy way to see why this might be is to 
              think about using it for some value of <m>t</m> that corresponds to one 
              week after the most recent interest payment. Since this value of <m>t</m>
              would be larger than it was when that interest payment was made, the 
              amount in the account would, according to the formula, be larger too. But
              the amount in the account does not actually change until the next interest 
              payment, roughly three weeks after this. So the theoretical amount suggested
              by the formula only matches the true amount in the account at those moments 
              when an interest payment has just been added to the account. That is,
              only for those moments when <m>t</m> is something equally divisible
              by <m>\frac{1}{n}=\frac{1}{12}</m>.
            </p>
            <exercises xml:id="exercises-interest">
              <exercisegroup>
              
                <introduction>
                  <p>
                    For the following problems, the savings account
                    in the Alsaka Credit Union
                    has an APR of 4%, compounded monthly.
                  </p>
                </introduction>
              
                <exercise>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Casper just won a tennis tournament and wants
                      to place his prize money in a savings account 
                      in the Alsaka Credit Union. He deposits $4000
                      into the account and then forgets about it for
                      eight years. How much money is waiting for him
                      when he finally remembers about the account? 
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                  <answer>
                    <p>
                      Casper will have $5505.58 in eight years.
                    </p>
                  </answer>
                </exercise>                
                
                <exercise>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      Ana wants to save up money to take a fancy vacation,
                      but she won't have enough release time from her job 
                      until three years from today. She has quite a bit of
                      spare cash at the moment and would like to deposit
                      some of that cash into an Alsaka Credit Union savings
                      account so that it will have grown to $5000 in four 
                      years.
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                  <hint>
                    <p>
                      If you write down the usual equation, which variables
                      have values that have been provided to you and which
                      one does not? If there is only one variable whose value
                      you do not know, how might you determine the
                      value of that variable?
                    </p>
                  </hint>
                  <answer>
                    <p>
                      Ana should deposit $4435.49.
                    </p>
                  </answer>
                </exercise>                
                
                <exercise>
                  <statement>
                    <p>
                      A deposit of $1000 was placed into an account for Franz
                      at Alsaka Credit Union. His father says that he can only
                      withdraw money from the account when the amount has
                      increased to $3000. If Franz only checks at the end of
                      each year, how many years will he have to wait before
                      he can withdraw some money?
                    </p>
                  </statement>
                  <hint>
                    <p>
                      One way to approach this is to try various values for <m>t</m>.
                      Or you could use a spreadsheet program and build a table
                      with these values. Or, as with the previous problem, you could
                      fill in the values of all the variables you know and see if
                      there is some way to use algebra to find the value of the one
                      variable you do not know. (This requires the use of logarithms,
                      which you may never have seen.)
                    </p>
                  </hint>
                </exercise>
              
              </exercisegroup>
            </exercises>
          </subsection>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-yield">
            <title>Annual Yield</title>
            <p>
              Despite APR being a (supposed) attempt at a clear
              numerical measure to be able to compare alternative
              savings or credit/loan opportunities, there remains
              some difficulty. 
              Since a savings account with 5% APR compounded monthly 
              will behave
              differently from a savings account 
              5% APR compounded quarterly (four
              times per year) it would be nice to have a measure
              that distinguishes between the two of them. In fact, 
              it can be even more tricky. For example, money
              grows faster in a account with an APR of 8%
              compounded daily than in an account with an APR
              of 8.05% compounded quarterly! (How would you
              convince yourself that this is true?)
            </p>        
            <p>
              One way to resolve this is, as is so often, to
              find a common perspective from which to view the
              situation. In this case, we will focus on the
              growth of money over the course of a year. That is,
              we will introduce the idea of 
              <term>annual yield</term>. Yield is, of course, a new 
              word for us in this context. Among other connotations
              it includes a hint of agricultural meaning. We can
              imagine the idea of sowing a certain amount of seed
              in a field and then checking, upon harvest, how much 
              more of the crop we have been able to produce. The 
              idea is no more complex than this: if some amount
              of money was placed into this account for a year,
              by what percent will it have increased?
            </p>
            <p>
              Equivalently: what annual effective interest rate would
              grow the money at the same (yearly) rate as the given
              APR? If we know the APR, <m>r</m>, the 
              number of times compounded per year for the APR, <m>n</m>,
              then we seek some annual effective interest rate, <m>i</m>, 
              which grows the money at an equivalent rate over the 
              course of one year.
              This immediately suggests the equation that we  
              should set up: the left side of the equation
              is the amount function for APR and the right side
              is the accumulation function for an annual effective
              interest rate:
              <me>
                P_0\left( 1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^{nt}=P_0(1+i)^t
              </me>
              But we can make this even easier to solve. We have
              already said we are seeking equivalence over the course
              of a single year, which means we set <m>t=1</m>. 
              Better still, since <m>P_0</m> is on each side of the 
              equation, it can be divided away! (This makes sense
              because we are only seeking the percent change
              over the course of the year, and the percent change 
              would be the same for a deposit of $1 as it would for
              a deposit of $1000 or $1,000,000.) Thus:
              <me>
                \left( 1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^n=1+i
              </me>
              And since we seek <m>i</m> and have been provided with
              <m>r</m> and <m>n</m>, we thus have a formula for
              <m>i</m> simply by subtracting 1 from each side of the 
              equation:
              <men xml:id="eqn-yield-from-apr">
                i=\left( 1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^n-1
              </men>
              As is often the case, we might also sometimes want to know
              what APR would realize some given yield. We can also answer
              this quickly, though it requires finding an <m>n</m>th 
              root. 
              <men xml:id="eqn-apr-from-yield">
                r=n\left((1+i)^{\frac{1}{n}}-1\right)
              </men>
              Consider the following examples to see more about the use of each.
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-yield-from-apr">
              <title>Finding the Annual Yield from APR</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Alyosha has been instructed by his monastery
                  to invest some of the order<rsq/>s funds
                  into a savings account which has an annual yield
                  of at least 5.25%. The nearby Leningrad Credit Union
                  offers a savings account with a 5.2% APR compounded
                  daily (that is, 365 times per year). Can Alyosha 
                  invest the monastery<rsq/>s funds there? 
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Yes. The annual yield is approximately 5.337%.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Use <xref ref="eqn-yield-from-apr"/> and set
                  <m>r=0.052</m> and <m>n=365</m>.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>

            <example xml:id="apr-from-yield">
              <title>Finding the APR that will generate some Annual Yield</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Ivan believes in the existence of a savings account
                  that will pay interest, compounded monthly, at an 
                  APR that will generate an annual yield of 8%. He 
                  learns of a credit union in Moscow that has a monthly
                  APR. What percent monthly APR would justify Ivan's 
                  belief?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  An APR of approximately 7.72%, compounded monthly,
                  will have an annual yield of 8%.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Use <xref ref="eqn-yield-from-apr"/> and set
                  <m>i=0.08</m> and <m>n=12</m>.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>

          </subsection>

        </section>
        <section xml:id="sec-loans">
          <title>Understanding Loans</title>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              We have spent quite some time on savings accounts and 
              using that context to understand interest in general. The hope
              is that we may now lean on the beginnings of your intuition
              about interest as we move into the more complex financial
              objects: loans.
            </p>
            <p>
              We will use the terms <term>borrower</term> and 
              <term>lender</term> throughout this section. The
              borrower receives an amount of cash in the present.
              They get money right now, in return for a promise
              that they will pay money back to the lender in the
              future. The repayment might take place all at once
              or might be accomplished by a series of payments,
              and these payments in turn might all be the same
              amount or they might change in amount over time.
              As long as we are careful about how we think about
              the agreement between the two parties, we will be
              able to understand how these payments can be in
              alignment with agreed-upon interest rates associated
              with the loan.
            </p>
            <p>
              Loans are an almost inescapable fact of modern life 
              under capitalism. The granting or refusal to grant 
              loans is a sometimes brutal expression of power, with
              effects upon whether families can secure reliable housing.
              Historically, this tool has been wielded in biased ways.
              It is still wielded in biased ways. (We will discuss ideas
              around credit scores and risk analysis in
              <xref ref="ch-probability"/>.)
            </p>
            <p>
              The chances are good you and your family are already
              enmeshed in loan agreements, whether related to housing or 
              also possibly related to your payments for your education.
            </p>
          </introduction>
          
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-single-payment">
            <title>Single Payment Loans</title>
            <p>
              A loan is merely a financial agreement. Money is provided
              in the present by one party, the lender, and this money is
              given to the other party, the borrower. It is agreed between
              the two parties
              that the borrower will provide money at one or more times
              in the future. A loan is nothing more than this. We will
              bring in ideas of interest and even more complicated thinking
              but in the end a loan is only this: the borrower receives
              money now
              and will return money in the future. If you give your 
              friend $1000 and they say, 
              <q>
                I'll pay you back $1100 in a couple years,
              </q>
              then the two of you have agreed upon a loan. The 
              conditions described do <em>imply</em> an annual 
              interest rate for that loan (or even imply a monthly
              APR, if you wanted to think it through that way) but
              the two of you need not ever name or even think about
              the interest involved. You have agreed upon what each
              of you will do, so the situation
              is a loan. 
            </p>
            <p>
              When, as described, the loan consists only of two 
              payments, one in each direction, the situation is 
              essentially equivalent to the savings account
              examples we saw in <xref ref="sec-interest"/>.
              Remember, when one places money into a savings 
              account one is loaning money to the bank!
            </p>
            <remark>
              <p>
                Just think how much ideological effort has
                gone into getting us all to think about the
                bank as serving the customer when in fact
                it is receiving a loan from us. Once you 
                begin thinking carefully about these 
                processes it becomes impossible to ignore how
                much shaping of our thought has taken place 
                down through the years.                  
              </p>
            </remark>
            <p>
              Since it is the same situation, we need not build
              up any new apparatus to answer such a question.
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-single-payment-loan">
              <title>A Loan under Compound Interest with Single Repayment</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Bildad hates to borrow money, but he really needs a new
                  sail for his whaling ship. He can get one and get it fitted
                  to his ship for $200. His colleague Peleg agrees to loan 
                  the $200, to be repaid after three years when the ship
                  returns with its valuable cargo. Considering the risk 
                  involved the pair agree that an interest rate of
                  6%, compounded once at the end of each year, seems fair. 
                  How much money
                  will Bildad pay Peleg in three years to satisfy the 
                  requirements of the loan?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Bildad will pay Peleg $238.20.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  Recall what we said about changing perspectives:
                  We are really asking how much Peleg will have in
                  a savings account after three years if he is
                  receiving a compound interest payment of 6% 
                  at the end of each year. The deposit is the
                  amount paid to Bildad, $200. The number of 
                  interest periods is three, since the interest is
                  charged each year. Thus, 
                  <m>r=0.06, P_0=200, t=2</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  So, using our formula in this new context we 
                  get:
                  <me>
                    P=P_0(1+r)^t=200(1+0.06)^3=238.20.
                  </me>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              A more usual situation for loans is that the single
              payment to the borrower in the present is balanced
              by multiple future payments. Let us begin to explore 
              these now.
            </p>
          </subsection>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-interest-payment">
            <title>Making Interest Payments Along the Way</title>
            <p>
              A somewhat unusual way to repay a loan is described 
              in this section. We will not explore it deeply, but
              it is included in the hope that understanding the
              logic of this approach to repayment will help
              ground future intuition about more complicated 
              repayment schemes.
            </p>
            <p>
              As always, remember that when
              we speak of <q>logic</q> in this context, we are 
              referring to analysis of a hoped-for (or purported?)
              internal coherence of the practices surrounding these 
              financial instruments, not endorsing the practices
              as natural or moral or efficient or good.
            </p>
            <p>
              If we think about Bildad and Peleg and their agreement
              in <xref ref="ex-single-payment-loan"/>, we can imagine 
              Peleg perhaps having second thoughts. As they sit across
              from each other, Peleg imagines that it might be nice 
              to receive some small amounts of money in the meantime
              so that he can take care of maintenance of his own
              around the boatyard or the house. They already have an
              agreement about the interest rate, no reason to
              reopen all of that negotiation. But Peleg might
              ask that Bildad pay the interest payments at the end of
              each year. How would this then play out?
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-interest-only-loan">
              <title>Interest-Only Payments on a Loan</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Bildad has borrowed $200 and agreed to pay the
                  6% annual interest at the end of each year as 
                  well as the
                  full amount at the end of the loan, after 
                  three years. What payments
                  are made by Bildad to Peleg and when does he make
                  them?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Bildad pays $12 after one year, $12 after two
                  years, and $212 after three years.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  At 6% per year, Bildad will owe Peleg how much
                  at the end of the first year? We can use the usual
                  formula:
                  <me>
                    P=200(1+.06)^1=200(1.06)=200+12=212
                  </me>
                  Note the third step in our arithmetic: 
                  <m>200+12</m>.
                  Here we can see an important distinction: 
                  there is the original loan amount, $200, 
                  and the interest amount at that moment 
                  in time, $12. As we move deeper into examination
                  of loans, we will need to pay close attention
                  to this sort of distinction. The point is that
                  in this payment scheme, Bildad makes a payment
                  of $12 which reduces the amount he owes, at that
                  moment, to the original $200. The interest then
                  begins growing once more. We will often say that 
                  the interest <term>accrues</term>. 
                </p>
                <p>
                  Interestingly, we could think of the loan restarting
                  at this moment only now as a two-year loan at an annual
                  rate of 6%. After another year, once again Bildad
                  owes Peleg $212 and makes a payment of $12 to reduce
                  the <term>outstanding loan balance</term> to $200 once
                  more. 
                </p>
                <p>
                  The last year is slightly different, though not in
                  how the interest accrues. Once more the loan balance
                  grows from $200 to $212. Bildad now owes that full amount
                  since the agreement was that the loan would be fully
                  paid off after three years. It is still correct to think
                  of this payment as made up of $12 of interest and the 
                  remaining $200 as the original loan amount.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              Before we move on to yet another form of loan repayment,
              we should compare the two situations we have seen thus
              far, in <xref ref="ex-single-payment-loan"/> and in 
              <xref ref="ex-interest-only-loan"/>. 
              Specifically, let us 
              consider how much money Bildad paid to Peleg in total
              under each of these payment schemes. 
            </p>
            <p>
              In <xref ref="ex-single-payment-loan"/> Bildad paid 
              $238.20 at the end of the process and no other payments.
              Bildad, thus, paid back $38.20 beyond the amount he
              received at the beginning of the process. But in the 
              second payment scheme, in 
              <xref ref="ex-interest-only-loan"/>, Bildad paid $12, 
              then $12 more, then $212. This is a total of $236 repaid
              to Peleg. How are we to make sense of this if, in each
              case, a 6% annual rate of interest was in effect?  
            </p>
            <p>
              Perhaps you have an intuition: if we take the lens on
              interest which views it
              as the price paid by the borrower for control of the
              money in question, then in this case Bildad, in the second
              case, returned control of some of the money earlier in
              the process. So since Peleg gains control of $12 after
              one year and another $12 after two years, then the total
              <q>price</q> to Bildad for use of the original $200 drops
              to a total of $36 rather than the $38.20 he had to pay 
              under the original scheme. We call this number the 
              <term>total interest</term> or 
              <term>total interest paid</term> and it is always the 
              difference found by summing all cash payments and then
              subtracting from that sum the original loan amount.
            </p>
            <p>
              We can also make sense of the difference
              between the two amounts of total interest in this case 
              by viewing through the lens of
              risk. By receiving some of the repayment money before the 
              end of the loan term, Peleg has slightly reduced risk. Think
              of it as a reduction in risk of total loss. Since this 
              payment scheme is slightly less risky for Peleg, Bildad 
              can pay slightly less overall for the chance to use the 
              loan money.
            </p>
            <p>
              The other thing that is made more clear by consideration
              of this scheme for repaying a loan is this: it might be 
              quite a challenge to have the cash on hand for the 
              large payment at the end of this process. It is helpful
              to have repaid some amount along the way to help reduce
              the final payment and reduce the total payment as well.
              But once we have begun to consider alternative ways to 
              repay a loan under the logic of interest that we have
              described here, it is worth considering just how 
              creative we might attempt to be.
            </p>
            <p>
              In particular, from the point of view of the borrower,
              why should the intermediate payments be so small that 
              they only cover the interest accrued? Perhaps it would
              make sense for Bildad to pay not just the $12, but 
              some extra amount to reduce the outstanding loan balance
              as well.
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-loan-many-payments">
              <title>Bildad Repaying the Loan with a Little Extra Each Time</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Suppose Bildad and Peleg change the 
                  loan agreement yet again.
                  The loan will still be for $200. 
                  The annual interest rate will remain 6%, as will the 
                  agreement that payments should happen at the end of the
                  first, second, and third years. Suppose Bildad suggests
                  that the payments at the end of the first and second 
                  years should be $40. Then what should the final payment
                  be and how much total interest will Bildad have paid? 
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  The final payment will be $150.86.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  If Bildad paid $40 at the end of the first year,
                  then $12 of that would pay the interest that had accrued
                  while the other $28 would reduce the original loan 
                  amount. This would have the additional benefit that now,
                  as of that moment, Bildad would only owe Peleg $172, since
                  <m>200-28=172</m>. This, in turn, would mean that the 
                  6% annual rate would create a smaller amount of interest
                  when the end of the second year arrived. Bildad would
                  only owe <m>172(0.06)=10.32</m> dollars in interest at
                  the end of the second year, which, combined with the 
                  previous year<rsq/>s loan balance of $172 would mean
                  a total of $182.32. Another way to see this same 
                  perspective is: 
                  <me>
                    P=172(1+0.06)^1=172+10.32=182.32
                  </me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  At the end of the second year, then,
                  when Bildad makes his payment of $40, 
                  the amount he owes will drop from $182.32
                  to $142.32. If we wish to think about how his
                  $40 payment was divided, $10.32 of it went to 
                  cover the new interest from that year, with the other
                  $29.68 coming off the (previous) balance of 
                  once the $172.
                </p>
                <p>
                  What happens to finish the process? Once again,
                  over the course of this last year, the loan balance
                  increases according to the 6% annual interest rate. 
                  So at the end of the process, after three years, 
                  the final amount owed will be 
                  <m>142.32(1.06)=150.8592</m> which rounds to the
                  nearest cent as $150.86. This is the amount of the
                  final payment to Peleg. $8.54 of this final payment
                  is for interest.
                </p>
                <p>
                  There are two ways to compute the total interest paid.
                  First, we can simply sum the total payments and subtract
                  the original loan amount. This us usually the easiest way
                  to find total interest paid. In this case, the total 
                  payments are <m>40+40+150.86=230.86</m>. Thus, the
                  total interest paid is <m>230.86-200=30.86</m> dollars.
                  Equivalently, since we have already gone to the trouble
                  of noting how much of each payment went to interest, we
                  could add up those portions attributable to interest along
                  the way. It should give us the same answer. And, indeed,
                  <m>12+10.32+8.54=30.86</m> does indeed give us the same 
                  amount of total interest. Notice also that this amount is
                  smaller than the amounts of total interest paid in
                  <xref ref="ex-single-payment-loan"/> and 
                  <xref ref="ex-interest-only-loan"/>. This should agree
                  with your intuition, since this sequence of payments 
                  returns still more of the loaned money to the control of 
                  Peleg earlier in the process, meaning Bildad can
                  logically pay a smaller total price 
                  (for reasons of risk reduction for Peleg
                  or for reasons of increased earlier control of cash for Peleg).
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
          </subsection>
          <p>
            Before we move on to develop the approach to level-payment
            loan repayment schemes, we need to build up a little more
            theory around the interaction between money and time
            under the logic of some fixed interest rate.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-time-value">
          <title>The Time Value of Money</title>
          <p>
            Before we leave the topic of money and interest and the
            systems within which we are enmeshed, let us gather the
            ideas into a sort of coherent approach. The fact that the
            entire structure is formed by human habit and choice need
            not prevent us from thinking through how its logic can be
            extended into more ornate systems of payments. If we can 
            understand this, we can understand a whole variety of 
            financial tools.
          </p>
          <p>
            To keep things simple, throughout this section we will
            carry out our analysis in somewhat generic terms, where
            interest <m>i</m> is compounded per time period. The most
            common such periods would be year or month. Most of our 
            examples will be presented in terms of years.
          </p>
          <p>
            The fundamental question that drives the entire logic of
            the following tools is this: How valuable is it, right now,
            to have the right to receive some fixed amount of money 
            at a fixed moment in the future? A more specific version
            of this question: how much should you pay, now, to receive 
            $100 in one year? 
          </p>
          <p>
            The answer depends on an interest rate! We seek a system,
            as we have discussed previously, that has a certain internal
            logic to it. This is not just some idealistic wish: in 
            a financial system that fails to fit together with this 
            sort of logic, there will be available certain no-risk 
            arrangements of payments with positive value, and this is
            viewed as
            a sort of inefficiency in the system. Such a no-risk way
            to make money is called an 
            <term>arbitrage opportunity</term> and they tend not to last
            long in the real financial/economic system. (There are whole 
            arrays of computers whose sole mission in life is to 
            spot such opportunities and automatically invest in them
            as swiftly and effectively as possible before they dissappear.)
            When we assume a certain interest rate, we can then discuss 
            the <term>present value</term> of some future cash flow or set
            of cash flows. We call this assumed interest rate the 
            <term>risk-free rate</term>. (Our analysis in this text 
            will only ever assume a single such rate. There is a whole
            fascinating world to explore once one allows for the more
            realistic situation of different rates available over 
            different amounts of time. But this is well beyond our
            set of concerns in this text.)
          </p>
          <p>
            So: if we assume that the risk-free interest rate is
            an annual effective interest rate of 5%, how 
            much should we pay right now to receive $100 in a year?
            The answer should look very familiar! This is the 
            same old question from earlier in this text, only 
            slightly disguised. We are asking how much should 
            be invested, right now, so that it will grow to $100
            at the end of the year. So using 
            <xref ref="eqn-apr-compound"/> 
            <me>
              P=P_0\left(1+\frac{r}{n}\right)^{nt}
            </me>
            with
            <m>r=0.05, n=1, t=1</m> and <m>P=100</m> we find:
            <me>
              100=P_0\left(1+\frac{0.05}{1}\right)^{(1)(1)}
            </me>
            This simplifies to:
            <me>
              100=P_0(1.05)
            </me>
            So we conclude that we should invest:
            <me>P_0=\dfrac{100}{1.05}=95.238095</me>
            which rounds to $95.24. But let us restate
            the key idea here:
            <em>
              The present value of a future cash payment is
              the amount that, if invested now at the risk-free
              rate, would grow under compound interest to
              equal that future cash payment at that future time.
            </em>
            So in this case the present value of $100 is $95.24, when 
            we assume a risk-free interest rate of 5% annual effective.
          </p>
          <p>
            To be clear: this rationale applies for all time intervals.
            So we can say that the value of a $100 payment in five years
            under 5% annual effective interest is:
            <me>
              PV=\dfrac{100}{(1+0.05)^5}=78.3526
            </me>
            Thus, the present value of $100 received in five years is
            $78.35 when 
            we assume a risk-free interest rate of 5% annual effective.
          </p>
          <p>
            There is one more very helpful fact about present values: 
            because we are generating them from a coherent set of 
            assumptions, grounded in mathematics, we can combine them
            easily as well using arithmetic.
          </p>
          <example>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Assuming 5% annual compound interest, what is the 
                present value of the right to be paid $100 in one
                year and another $100 in five years? 
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                The present value is $173.59.
              </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <me>
                  PV=\dfrac{100}{1+0.05}+\dfrac{100}{(1+0.05)^5}=173.59
                </me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </example>
          <p>
            The true power of this perspective on understanding
            the value of cash flows is this: we need not be limited
            by only the present value. In fact, by thinking of
            this logic carefully, we can shift our perspective, 
            as needed, to find the value of series of cash
            flows at <em>any</em> point in time. It is true that,
            for the topics treated here, we can resolve most of our
            questions in the present, using present value, which is
            the value of the cash flows at time <m>t=0</m>. But if 
            judging the value of a cash flow at a different point in
            time is nothing more than multiplying or dividing by
            the appropriate version of <m>(1+i)^n</m> then we have
            some true flexibility.
          </p>
          <principle xml:id="principle-time-value-of-money">
            <statement>
              <p>
                The value of a cash flow of 
                <m>C</m> dollars arriving at time
                <m>t=T_1</m>, where <m>t</m> is measured in the
                natural unit of the interest period used for the 
                risk-free effective interest rate <m>i</m>, 
                can be determined for any other time <m>t=T_0</m>.
                The value at <m>T_0</m>, <m>V_{T_0}</m>, is
                <me>
                  V_{T_0}=C(1+i)^{T_1-T_0}
                </me>
                Note that this formula works if <m>T_1</m> is before 
                <m>T_0</m>, or if <m>T_1</m> is after <m>T_0</m>, 
                and even if <m>T_1=T_0</m>.
              </p>
            </statement>
          </principle>
          <p>
            More informally, this means that, once we have agreed upon
            a risk-free per-period interest rate <m>i</m> to use in 
            our analysis, we can view the value of money, moving
            through time, by multiplying or dividing by factors of
            <m>(1+i)</m>. 
            <dl>
              <li>
                <title>Value of a Cash Flow <m>n</m> Units of Time Later</title>
                <p>
                  A cash flow <m>C</m> has value 
                  <m>C(1+i)^n</m> <m>n</m> periods in the future. 
                  Multiplication by factors of <m>(1+i)</m>
                  moves the value forward in time.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <title>Value of a Cash Flow <m>n</m> Units of Time Earlier</title>
                <p>
                  A cash flow <m>C</m> has value 
                  <m>\dfrac{C}{(1+i)^n}</m> <m>n</m> periods in the 
                  past. Division by factors of <m>(1+i)</m>
                  moves the value backward in time.
                </p>
              </li>
            </dl>
          </p>
          <p>
            Let<rsq/>s solidify this idea with an example:
          </p>
          <example>
            <title>Values at Various Times</title>
            <statement>
              <p> For the following questions, use an 
                annual risk-free effective interest rate of 
                <m>i=0.04</m>.
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      What is the value two years from
                      now of a payment of $100 five years from
                      now?
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      What is the value in ten years
                      of a payment of $100 in three years?
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      What is the value in five years of 
                      a payment of $100 in three years and a
                      payment of $100 in ten years?
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      $88.90
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      $131.59
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      $190.35
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <ol>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      There are multiple ways for us to understand this. 
                      Perhaps the most useful for building intuition is this:
                      we can think about finding the present value (that is, 
                      the <m>t=0</m> value) of the payment, and then take that
                      present value and move it forward to the target time.
                      In other words we can think of selling the payment at
                      <m>t=5</m> right now, then taking that cash in the 
                      present and investing it at the risk-free rate for two
                      years until <m>t=2</m>. The present value of the payment
                      is:
                      <me>
                        PV=\dfrac{100}{(1+0.04)^5}=82.19
                      </me>
                      When this is then allowed to grow for two years at 4% annual
                      compound interest it grows to:
                      <me>
                        \left(\dfrac{100}{(1+0.04)^5}\right)(1+0.04)^2=\dfrac{100}{(1+0.04)^3}=88.90
                      </me>
                      We can also see that we get the same result by thinking
                      of the process as moving through time. The $100 at five
                      years, <m>t=5</m> must travel backwards by three years to
                      time <m>t=2</m>. To travel backwards, we divide by a power
                      of <m>(1+0.04)</m> and the appropriate power is given by
                      how many time periods we are traveling in the backwards 
                      direction. In this case, that is three years. Thus:
                      <me>
                        V_2=\dfrac{100}{(1+0.04)^3}=88.90
                      </me>
                      A final way to find this numerical value
                      is simply to insert the appropriate
                      values into the equation in
                      <xref ref="principle-time-value-of-money"/>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      This is perhaps a little more straightforward. Indeed,
                      this is a question we could have answered much
                      earlier in this chapter, simply by recognizing 
                      that this is $100 sitting in an account paying
                      4% compound interest for seven interest periods. We
                      somewhat naturally place ourselves at that moment
                      in time when the deposit is made. It is worth 
                      emphasizing, though, that this is what we are doing.
                      We need to feel more comfortable moving ourselves to
                      different temporal perspectives, specifically by
                      telling ourselves, we want to view this from <m>t=3</m>
                      or from <m>t=10</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      So one solution is just to write:
                      <me>
                        V_3=100(1+0.04)^7=131.59
                      </me>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      It is worth continuing to build our intuition, though. One
                      other perspective that leads us to the same answer:
                      first, find the present value of $100 by moving it back
                      to the present, which is back three years, by dividing 
                      by <m>(1+i)^3</m>, then moving that present value
                      forward by ten years by multiplying by <m>(1+i)^10</m>. 
                      This results in the same numerical value.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The final perspective, of course, is simply to insert the
                      appropriate values of <m>T_0, T_1, i</m>, and <m>C</m>
                      into <xref ref="principle-time-value-of-money"/>.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <p>
                      The important principle here is that, as with present
                      value, we can take the individual <m>t=5</m> point of view
                      on each of these payments and simply add them together
                      at that moment in time.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      So the <m>t=5</m> value of the payment in three
                      years is <m>100(1+0.04)^2=108.16</m> while the <m>t=5</m>
                      value of the payment in ten years is 
                      <m>\frac{100}{(1+0.04)^5}=82.19</m> and when we add
                      those we get $190.35.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      Finally, another perspective would be to bring everything 
                      back to present value, like so:
                      <me>
                        PV=\frac{100}{(1+0.04)^3}+\frac{100}{(1+0.04)^{10}}
                      </me>
                      Then we project that present value forward by five years
                      by multiplying by <m>(1+0.04)^5</m> which gives us:
                      <me>
                        V_5=(1+0.04)^5\left(\frac{100}{(1+0.04)^3}+\frac{100}{(1+0.04)^{10}}\right)
                      </me>
                      which then simplifies to:
                      <me>
                        V_5=100(1+0.04)^2+\frac{100}{(1+0.04)^5}
                      </me>
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </example>

          <p>
            Finally, because so many of our later applications
            involve a large number of equal cash payments 
            repeated at regular intervals, we will benefit from
            understanding one more formula. We wish to be able to
            easily compute the 
            present value of <m>n</m> future payments of  
            <m>Q</m> dollars. The payments are made at times
            <m>t=1, 2, \dots, n</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            As so often, we will start with a simple example.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="ex-pv-annuity">
            <title>Present Value of <m>4</m> Future Payments</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                Lana tells Sabrina she will pay her $200 at the end
                of each of the next four years. Sabrina says, 
                <q>
                  Okay, 
                  and I will loan you an amount of money now that 
                  means you will be paying me 2% annual interest.
                </q>
                They shake hands and Lana starts trying to decide 
                which Criterion Collection discs she will buy
                with the money. But how much can she spend based
                on what Sabrina just gave her? (She has already
                decided on <pubtitle>Matewan</pubtitle> and 
                <pubtitle>Portrait of a Lady on Fire</pubtitle> at
                the very least.)
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                Sabrina gave Lana $761.55.
              </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
              <p>
                Since we know that the present value of each payment
                can be found by dividing by some power of <m>(1+0.02)</m>
                and since we also know that we can simply sum up 
                these present values, the appropriate formula is:
                <me>
                  PV=\dfrac{200}{(1+0.02)}+\dfrac{200}{(1+0.02)^2}+\dfrac{200}{(1+0.02)^3}+\dfrac{200}{(1+0.02)^4}
                </me>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </example>
          <p>
            This sort of calculation is not so bad when there are only a few
            payments. But what about a large, long-term loan? These can routinely
            have 360 or 480 payments. You presumably do not have the patience
            (nor should you!)
            to write out 360 or 480 terms in a sum. Luckily, algebra can save
            us quite a bit of work.
          </p>
          <p>
            We can make use of a fact from algebra (which relies
            upon some rather deep principles from calculus) to 
            make things quite a bit nicer for ourselves. Namely,
            that the following equation is true as long as 
            <m>r \ne 1</m>:
            <men xml:id="eqn-polynomial-division">
              1+r+r^2+\cdots+r^{n-1}=\dfrac{1-r^n}{1-r}
            </men>
          </p>
          <p>
            Perhaps you can see how this helps. We want to
            know the present value of <em>any</em> number
            of equal future payments made at consistent 
            intervals. What would the long version of that
            look like? It would look like this (with our 
            usual variables of <m>i</m> for per-period interest
            rate, <m>Q</m> for the dollar amount of each payment, 
            and <m>N</m> for the total number of payments):
            <me>
              PV=\dfrac{Q}{(1+i)}+\dfrac{Q}{(1+i)^2}+\cdots + \dfrac{Q}{(1+i)^N}
            </me>
            This might not look so promising. But notice that every
            term has a factor of <m>\frac{Q}{(1+i)}</m> and if we factor
            this out from each term we get:
            <me>
              PV=\dfrac{Q}{(1+i)}\left(1+\dfrac{1}{(1+i)}+\dfrac{1}{(1+i)^2}+\cdots + \dfrac{1}{(1+i)^{N-1}}\right)
            </me>
            Which is only a small step from:
            <me>
              PV=\dfrac{Q}{(1+i)}\left(1+\left(\dfrac{1}{(1+i)}\right)+\left(\dfrac{1}{(1+i)}\right)^2+\cdots + \left(\dfrac{1}{(1+i)}\right)^{N-1}\right)
            </me>
            That portion inside the parentheses now looks promising! 
            As long as <m>i \ne 0</m>, we can
            rewrite it using <xref ref="eqn-polynomial-division"/> with 
            <m>r=\frac{1}{(1+i)}</m> and <m>n=N</m> and we get:  
            <me>
              PV=\dfrac{Q}{(1+i)}\left(\dfrac{1-(\frac{1}{1+i})^N}{1-\frac{1}{(1+i)}}\right)
            </me>
            If we then distribute the denominator and simplify the numerator we get:
            <me>
              PV=\dfrac{Q\left(1-(\frac{1}{1+i})^N\right)}{(1+i)-1}
            </me>
            which then simplifies to:
            <me>
              PV=\dfrac{Q\left(1-(\frac{1}{1+i})^N \right)}{i}=\dfrac{Q}{i}\left(1-\left(\frac{1}{1+i}\right)^N \right)
            </me>
            The most useful form of this formula is:
            <men xml:id="eqn-pv-many-future-payments">
              PV=\dfrac{Q \left((1+i)^N-1\right)}{i\left(1+i\right)^N}
            </men>
            We will build some quite useful future formulas
            from this relationship. It will be especially useful
            in our analysis of loans and their amortization.
          </p>
          <example xml:id="ex-pv-many-future-payments">
            <title>Present Value of Many Future Payments</title>
            <statement>
              <p>
                The Wild Heart Credit Union has agreed to loan
                money to Clarice at a 4% APR compounded monthly.
                Clarice will make monthly payments of $1200 for
                the next 30 years. What is the present value
                of these future payments which begin one month
                from now. This present value will constitute the
                <term>principal</term> of the loan, also often
                called the <term>loan amount</term>.
              </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
              <p>
                $251,353.49
              </p>
            </answer>
            <solution>
              <p>
                The first potential pitfall here is the interest rate.
                Since it is given to us as a monthly APR, we need to 
                transform it to a monthly effective interest rate. The 
                variable <m>i</m> in this formula must always be the 
                effective rate associated with the interval of time
                between payments. So, our effective rate can be found
                by <m>i=\frac{0.04}{12}</m>. Monthly payments for 30 years
                means <m>N=(12)(30)=360</m> total payments. Finally, 
                the payments are $1200 each, which means <m>Q=1200</m>.
                So when we plug all that into 
                <xref ref="eqn-pv-many-future-payments"/>, we get:
                <me>
                  PV=\dfrac{Q \left((1+i)^N-1\right)}{i\left(1+i\right)^N}=\dfrac{1200 \left((1+\frac{.04}{12})^{360}-1\right)}{(\frac{0.04}{12})\left(1+\frac{0.04}{12}\right)^{360}}
                </me>
                which means:
                <me>
                  PV=251{,}353.49
                </me>
                So the loan amount that Clarice has to use, now, in the present,
                is $251,353.49.
              </p>
            </solution>
          </example>
          <p>
            The formula allows us to understand the
            present value of large numbers of future payments, as long
            as the payments are equally spaced and the effective interest
            rate per period remains constant throughout the life of the 
            process. In fact, even if some payments are missed or if the 
            interest rate changes, we can, with some cleverness, still
            carry out this sort of analysis. But for now we are ready to
            move on to explore loans.
          </p>


          <exercises xml:id="exercises-time-value-money">
            <exercise>
              
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
              
            </exercise>
          </exercises>
        </section>

        <section xml:id="sec-amortized-loans">
          <title>Amortized Loans</title>
          <introduction>
            <p>
              In <xref ref="sec-loans"/> we learned about making
              interest payments in such a way that we could then
              make a final interest payment plus the originally
              loaned amount at the end of the process. This
              might be reasonable in some situations, but depending
              on the original loan amount, might be rather unreasonable.
              For example, if one were to use a loan to buy a house 
              for $700,000 (which is below the median sale price
              and below the median asking price in Seattle in 
              2025, according to Zillow) one would have to plan rather
              carefully to make sure one was able to make a payment of
              $700,000 (plus an interest payment!) 
              at the end of the loan period. Most people
              do not have this amount sitting around in their savings
              account. Further, such a large payment at the very end of
              the process makes the loan agreement more risky in the eyes
              of the granter of the loan. (What happens if the borrower
              refuses or cannot pay that extremely large last payment?)
            </p>
            <p>
              With this in mind, what is more usual is to spread out
              the intermittent payments so that they are all the same
              amount, or at least as close the same amount as is 
              possible. It turns out that the fact that all payments
              must be rounded to the nearest cent will have some effect
              on our quest for every payment to be exactly the same.
              (Why might this be?)
            </p>          
          </introduction>
          <subsection xml:id="subsec-level-payment-loans">
            <title>Level Payment Loans</title>
            <p>
              We will balance two important goals for ourselves
              in this section. First, we wish to learn how to 
              construct a loan. That is, we will establish how to
              set up a series of future payments,
              from borrower to creditor, that will have
              equal present value to the loan amount that will be
              given to the borrower in the present. Simply: 
              borrower gets money now, what money does the borrower
              pay in the future? Naturally, this will depend upon 
              how many future payments there are, how frequently 
              those future payments will occur, and what  
              effective interest rate, per payment period, is 
              in effect.
            </p>
            <p>
              The number of ways a loan could be repayed is essentially
              infinite, dependent only upon how creatively the 
              borrower and creditor wish to be in agreeing to the 
              exchange of payments. Note, also, that these two
              parties need not even ever mention an interest rate. 
              They could agree to the payments and simply shake 
              hands and move on. (It is true that once those payments
              have been agreed to there is some implied interest
              rate (or, weirdly, possibly more than one!)
              that goes along with the loan, but these sorts
              of calculations, at least from scratch, are beyond 
              the scope of this text.)
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-loan-zero">
              <title>A Loan Between Friends</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Agnes has a chance to make a short film
                  but needs another $1000. Her friend Jean-Luc can
                  spare the money now, and wants to be repaid 
                  in three payments: $333.33 at the end of the first year,
                  $333.33 at the end of the second year, and $333.34 at
                  the end of the third year. What interest rate is Jean-Luc
                  charging Agnes?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  The interest rate is 0%. 
                  They are friends, after all.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We can see the interest rate must be 0% 
                  precisely because the amount she repays is
                  exactly equal to the loan amount. Notice that,
                  though we will often seek to keep the payments
                  all of equal size, even for a short-term loan 
                  like this, it will not always be possible. This
                  is because we must round to the nearest cent.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>

            <p>
              More usually, there is a positive interest
              rate associated with a loan. Let us consider a 
              simple one.
            </p>

            <example xml:id="ex-loan-with-four-payments">
              <title>A Loan with Four Payments</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Werner needs $2000 to finish his documentary.
                  Lotte is a more established filmmaker and 
                  agrees to loan the money at only 1% annual
                  interest. The loan is to be repaid over four 
                  years and four payments, at the end of each 
                  year. The payments are to be as equal as 
                  possible.
                </p>
                <p>
                  What should the four payments be?
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  Werner should pay $512.56 for the first three years.
                  The final payment should be $512.57. (Note: an 
                  alternative would be $512.57 for the first three years,
                  followed by a final payment of $512.54.)
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  We must solve for <m>Q</m> in the following
                  equation:
                  <me>
                    2000=\frac{Q}{(1+0.01)^1}+\frac{Q}{(1+0.01)^2}+\frac{Q}{(1+0.01)^3}+\frac{Q}{(1+0.01)^4}
                  </me>
                  This may look slightly unpleasant, until one realizes that 
                  the <m>Q</m> can be factored out of each term on the left:
                  <me>
                    2000=Q\left(\frac{1}{(1+0.01)^1}+\frac{1}{(1+0.01)^2}+\frac{1}{(1+0.01)^3}+\frac{1}{(1+0.01)^4}\right)
                  </me>
                  Now we compute that number inside the parentheses (and you
                  will want to keep a lot of digits, generally, in such
                  cases) as 3.901965552. (This is the default number of digits
                  that a spreadsheet program and many calculators will return.)
                  <me>
                    2000=Q(3.901965552)
                  </me>
                  and thus:
                  <me>
                    Q=\frac{2000}{3.901965552}=512.5621878
                  </me>
                  So the level payment rounds to $512.56.
                </p>
                <p>
                  There is a slight complication here, though. When we 
                  check the present value of these payments, what happens?
                  <me>
                    PV=\frac{512.56}{(1+0.01)^1}+\frac{512.56}{(1+0.01)^2}+\frac{512.56}{(1+0.01)^3}+\frac{512.56}{(1+0.01)^4}
                  </me>
                  and thus:
                  <me>
                    PV=1999.9915
                  </me>
                  
                  This rounds to $1999.99. How do we correct for this? By
                  making an adjustment to the final payment. If we increase it
                  by a single cent we find:
                  <me>
                    PV=\frac{512.56}{(1+0.01)^1}+\frac{512.56}{(1+0.01)^2}+\frac{512.56}{(1+0.01)^3}+\frac{512.57}{(1+0.01)^4}
                  </me>
                  and thus:
                  <me>
                    PV=2000.0011
                  </me>
                  
                  Now the loan has been set up in such a way that it matches
                  the conditions set out at the start. The alternative 
                  payment scheme suggested above can be similiarly justified,
                  which is left to the reader.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              The unequal final payment, even on this loan with
              a limited number of payments, is an important thing to
              consider. It turns out that because the monetary system
              has the cent as its lowest denomination, every payment
              must be rounded to the nearest cent. This rounding,
              once it has occurred over some number of payments, 
              has a cumulative effect that must be accounted for.
              The most usual way to account for this is by making
              the final payment either larger, which is called
              a <term>balloon payment</term>, or smaller, which is 
              called a <term>drop payment</term>. You can probably 
              when each will occur. If the payments along the way were
              rounded down, then it is likely that a balloon payment
              will be needed. On the other hand, if they were
              rounded up along the way, a drop payment will suffice
              to fully retire the debt on the original loan amount 
              (which, remember, is also called the principal).
            </p>
            <p>
              The overarching principle remains consistent: we are
              seeking payments, as level as possible, that will
              have a present value that is equal, to the nearest 
              cent, to the original loan amount.
            </p>
            <p>
              The usual approach, in this case, is to find the level
              payment using the present value formula, which can be
              set up in a general way. (We solved it for this payment
              in <xref ref="ex-loan-with-four-payments"/> but we 
              can generalize what we did there.)
            </p>
            <p>
              Since <xref ref="eqn-pv-many-future-payments"/>
              <me>
                PV=\dfrac{Q \left((1+i)^N-1\right)}{i\left(1+i\right)^N}
              </me>
              can, in this context, be understood as an equation
              where the present value is the loan amount:
              <me>
                L=\dfrac{Q \left((1+i)^N-1\right)}{i\left(1+i\right)^N}
              </me>
              Now we may solve for <m>Q</m>, keeping in mind that because
              we will be rounding to the nearest cent, it will only
              tell us the correct payment for all but the last payment.
              (Remember, the last payment usually needs to be adjusted,
              up or down, 
              to allow the debt to be retired exactly with the last
              payment.)
            </p>
            <p>
              First we note that <m>Q</m> can be viewed as multiplied
              by the rest of the formula:
              <me>
                L=Q\dfrac{\left((1+i)^N-1\right)}{i\left(1+i\right)^N}
              </me>
              Then we can divide both sides by that large complicated
              fraction which leaves the level payment alone (once we also
              swap the sides of the equation for easier reading):
              <me>
                Q=\dfrac{L}{\frac{(1+i)^N-1}{i(1+i)^N}}
              </me>
              This can be simplified if one recalls algebraic rules about dividing
              by a fraction:
              <men xml:id="eqn-loan-level-payment">
                Q=\dfrac{L(i\left(1+i\right)^N)}{(1+i)^N-1}
              </men>
              Once the majority of the level payments have been 
              computed in this way, the final payment can be computed
              by making sure that the present value (that is, for 
              <m>t=0</m>) of all the payments, including the last 
              one, equals the original loan amount.
            </p>

            <exercises xml:id="exercises-level-payment-loans">
              <exercise>
                
