              <exercise>
                
              </exercise>
            </exercises>
          </subsection>

          <subsection xml:id="subsec-loan-balance">
            <title>Outstanding Loan Balance During the Loan Term</title>
            <p>
              When we speak of the <term>amortization</term> of a
              loan, this refers to our ability to discern, throughout
              the process of repaying the loan, the current state
              of how much is owed, and, based on this, how each
              payment is split into one portion that covers the newly
              accrued interest and another portion that reduces the 
              original amount owed. In some ways, this might seem
              to be merely additional bookkeeping without much purpose.
              After all, once the two parties have agreed upon a 
              repayment scheme, what else is there to know?
            </p>
            <p>
              But of course, situations can change. What happens 
              if the buyers who are living in the house
              must move to another city? Then the house will often
              need to be sold. If the house is sold for $700,000 and
              the buyers used a loan to purchase the home for $600,000
              four years ago, what should happen? The buyers
              have been making payments and, in usual cases, those
              payments will have consistently exceeded what they
              owed in interest, so the original amount they owe to
              the bank should now be less than $600,000. But how much
              less? 
            </p>
            <p>
              In simplest terms, and leaving aside the 
              infamous <q>closing costs</q> (which can be accounted
              for later, once we have understood the basics) the original
              buyers, who are now selling the home for $700,000, will take
              some of that $700,000 to pay off their remaining debt
              to the bank. The rest, beyond that amount, they get to keep.
              Often they will need this money to put forward toward their
              next house, but the money is theirs to use how they see fit.
            </p>
            <p>
              We are left, then, with the question of how to determine
              how much of the house is owned by the bank and how much
              is owned by the buyers at any moment along the way.
              Well, perhaps not at <em>any</em> moment. We will focus on
              determining what the <term>outstanding loan balance</term>
              is in the instant just after a payment has been made.
            </p>
            <p>
              There are two ways we can determine the current outstanding
              loan balance. Though one will usually be easier to 
              compute than the other, the ability to understand the 
              rational basis for each, within this overarching system of
              credit and debt, will help to solidify our intuition about
              the system. 
            </p>
            <definition xml:id="def-olb-prospective">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  The outstanding loan balance (prospective version)
                  just after the <m>n</m>th payment 
                  is defined to be the <m>t=n</m>
                  present value
                  of the remaining payments, under the effective
                  per period interest rate of the original loan
                  agreement. Thus if the level payments are <m>Q</m>
                  dollars, the last payment is <m>R</m>, the total number
                  of payments is <m>N</m>, and 
                  the per-period interest rate is <m>i</m>, then the 
                  outstanding loan balance is:
                  <men xml:id="eqn-olb-prospective">
                    OLB_{pro}=\dfrac{Q \left((1+i)^{(N-n-1)}-1\right)}{i(1+i)^{(N-n-1)}}+\dfrac{R}{(1+i)^{(N-n)}}
                  </men>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            <p>
              This is called the prospective version because it
              is <q>looking forward</q> at the future payments.
              Now, this could be quite a tedious computation, if not for
              the fact that we derived and understood 
              <xref ref="eqn-pv-many-future-payments"/>. Indeed, the 
              computation shown in <xref ref="ex-pv-many-future-payments"/>
              serves as an excellent first example of computing
              an outstanding loan balance in this way. After all, the
              original loan amount, or principal, is also always the
              first outstanding loan balance.
            </p>
            <p>
              But perhaps you have already noticed a slight problem here.
              The formula we use for the present value of a large number
              of future payments relies upon all of those payments being
              exactly equal. Yet we have seen that even in relatively 
              short-term loans, we quickly arrive at a situation where
              the final payment has to be adjusted up or down to fully
              retire the debt. There are ways to adjust for this, but
              they can be somewhat algebraically and conceptually complex.
            </p>
            <p>
              We can avoid this complexity by using the retrospective
              (that is, <q>looking backwards</q>) version of outstanding
              loan balance.
            </p>
            <definition xml:id="def-olb-retrospective">
              <statement>
                <p>
                  The outstanding loan balance (retrospective version)
                  just after the <m>n</m>th payment,
                  can be found by computing 
                  the <m>t=0</m>
                  present value of all payments made so far,
                  subtracting this present value 
                  from the original loan amount,
                  and then computing the <m>t=n</m> value of 
                  this difference under the effective
                  per period interest rate of the original loan
                  agreement. Thus if the payments are <m>Q</m>
                  dollars, the per-period interest rate is <m>i</m>,
                  and the original loan amount is <m>L</m> then the 
                  outstanding loan balance is:
                  <men xml:id="eqn-olb-retro">
                    OLB_{retro}=(1+i)^n\left(L - \dfrac{Q \left((1+i)^n-1\right)}{i(1+i)^n}\right)
                  </men>
                </p>
              </statement>
            </definition>
            <p>
              
            </p>
            <p>
              One last way of thinking of the retrospective
              version of the outstanding loan balance is as follows. This
              way of computing gives an equivalent amount as the one
              given in <xref ref="def-olb-retrospective"/> but some may
              find this way of thinking of the computation as more intuitive.
              The intuition here is the following:
              Take the original loan amount, think about how it would
              have grown, absent any payments, in the time so far.
              <me>
                L(1+i)^n
              </me>
              This is the amount that would be owed at time <m>t=N</m>
              if no payments had been made. But they have been made! 
              So how do we give credit for those payments? We find
              their present value at <m>t=0</m> using our standard
              present value formula, 
              <xref ref="eqn-pv-many-future-payments"/>, and then we
              move this forward in time to <m>t=N</m>. This number can 
              then be subtracted from the moved-forward value of 
              the original loan
              amount. 
              <me>
                OLB_{retro}=L(1+i)^n - \left(\dfrac{Q \left((1+i)^n-1\right)}{i\left(1+i\right)^n}\right)(1+i)^n
              </me>  
            </p>
            <p>
              Once this perspective has been unlocked, this ability
              to say, coherently, in touch with all the particulars
              of the financial agreement, how much is owed at
              any point in the process, we can answer
              all sorts of other questions. We can, for example, 
              determine just how much of each payment is going
              towards interest and how much towards the principal.
              This can be interesting from a bookkeeping perspective
              and does, in the USA, sometimes have tax implications.
              But our primary interest in being able to find the 
              outstanding loan balance was to be able to asnwer
              questions about how to adjudicate questions of who
              owns how much of the asset in the in-between time
              when the loan is not fully paid off.
            </p>
            <p>
              We will explore these questions in the next section.
            </p>
          </subsection>

          <subsection xml:id="subsec-loan-refinance">
            <title>How and Why to Refinance a Loan</title>
            <p>
              We will approach the final question around 
              loans with a two-stage approach. First, we will
              establish how to make sense of a situation where
              the underlying asset (usually a house) is sold while
              the loan is still being paid off. The reason, again,
              why this can be a somewhat complicated situation is
              that at this moment part of the house belongs to the
              person paying off the loan and part of the house 
              belongs to the bank. (We are leaving aside a detailed
              analysis of the underlying legal framework to keep
              the discussion of the financial aspect as clear as
              possible.) 
            </p>
            <p>
              The good news is that understanding this situation 
              only relies upon careful deployment of the ideas we 
              have already developed. So let us begin with an
              example:
            </p>
            <example xml:id="ex-sell-house">
              <title>Selling a House During the Loan Term</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Amanda and Naomi bought their home over nine years ago
                  using a 30-year $400,000 loan from Fedal Credit Union.
                  The APR for their loan is 5% compounded monthly. They are 
                  making monthly payments of $2,147.29. Their final
                  payment will be $2,144.37.
                  If they sell the house for $500,000 just after their 111th
                  payment, how much of that money must they pay to the bank
                  to pay off their loan and how much are they left with?
                  (There are various legal and processing fees usually
                  called <q>closing costs</q> but we will ignore them for
                  now.)
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                 They must pay $332,345.85 to the bank and have $167,654.15
                 remaining afterwards.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  The whole question hinges on how much of the loan
                  remains to be paid, that is, on the outstanding 
                  loan balance just after the 111th payment. We can 
                  compute that using either 
                  <xref ref="eqn-olb-prospective"/> or
                  <xref ref="eqn-olb-retro"/>. From the description
                  of the loan in the problem we know that there will
                  be <m>N=12(30)=360</m> total payments. The payment
                  amounts will usually be <m>Q=2147.29</m> and the last
                  payment will be <m>R=2144.37</m>. The original loan
                  amount is <m>L=400{,}000</m>. Finally, the per-interval
                  effective interest rate is <m>i=\frac{0.05}{12}</m> and
                  we know we are looking for the outstanding loan balance
                  just after the 111th payment, so <m>n=111</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Once those values are provided to either of the 
                  outstanding loan balance formulas we find that that 
                  balance is $332,345.85.
                </p>
                <p>
                  From here, the last step is simple. They have just received
                  $500,000 and they owe $332,345.85. To find what is left over
                  we need only subtract:
                  <me>
                    500000-332345.85=167654.15
                  </me>
                  So Amanda and Naomi have $167,654.15 available to them,
                  either to put towards their next home or to use for other
                  purposes.
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              Now that we have a rationale for how to understand
              a current state of affairs partway through a loan
              payment process, we are prepared to understand one
              last key process. Once more, we will discuss this 
              in the specific context of a home loan, but the 
              principles would apply without adjustment to
              other loans.
            </p>
            <p>
              We have restricted our exploration of financial
              matters using the somewhat artificial assumption
              of a relatively static financial reality. In fact,
              there are many financial institutions, offering many
              different sorts of loans or lines of credit. Conditions
              change over time as well, each economic forecast 
              altering the financial landscape, nudging interest
              rates up or down.
            </p>
            <p>
              And when interest rates decrease? That may provide
              an opportunity for someone currently paying off a loan.
              If you are paying off a loan with an APR of 5% monthly
              and find yourself with a chance to borrow money for 
              4% monthly, there is a chance you can reduce your payments
              or decrease the number of future payments and pay 
              off your loan early. How? By taking out a new loan at the
              lower rate. (Because of the previously mentioned closing
              costs for a loan, it will not be quite so simple as merely
              comparing the rates. This is why we say there is a chance
              rather than a certainty of a benefit.)
            </p>
            <p>
              This all relies upon the work we did in developing 
              our understanding of the outstanding loan balance
              partway through the process of paying off an 
              amortized loan. Because we can say how much debt 
              remains at any intermediate point along the way
              of the repayment process, the debtor can be looking
              around for other loans that might be used to pay
              off that debt in an advantageous way.
            </p>
            <p>
              But let us explore this by way of a couple examples.
            </p>
            <example>
              <title>Refinancing with a Lower Interest Rate: Lowering Payments</title>
              <statement>
                <p>
                  Carlos, Jan, and Felix bought a house 11
                  years ago, and their 40-year loan with
                  monthly payments was for $500,000. They 
                  found a rate of 6% compounded monthly. The
                  level payments are $2751.07 with a final 
                  drop payment of $2747.49. The Rosethorn
                  Credit Union is offering a monthly APR
                  of 4.5% on montly-payment loans with term 
                  length 30 years or less. The friends wish
                  to refinance their loan by paying off their 
                  current loan balance with a new loan at Rosethorn.
                  The new loan will be a 29-year loan to cover the exact
                  outstanding loan balance just after the 132nd payment.
                  What is the loan amount (that is, the outstanding loan
                  balance) for the new loan and what will the new
                  monthly payments be? (Challenge: what would be the
                  drop or balloon payment at the end of the new loan?)
                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
                  The outstanding loan balance is $453,219.98, which is also
                  the principal for the new loan. The level payments will be
                  $2334.05 (with a final balloon payment of $2335.92).
                  They reduced their monthly payments by over $400.
                </p>
              </answer>
              <solution>
                <p>
                  To find the outstanding loan balance after the 132nd 
                  payment we can, in this case, use either 
                  <xref ref="eqn-olb-prospective"/> or
                  <xref ref="eqn-olb-retro"/> since we have been
                  told the amount of the final payment. (If we only
                  knew the level payments we would have to use
                  the retrospective approach.) By using the variable
                  values <m>i=\frac{0.06}{12}, N=12(40)=480, L=500000, Q=2751.07</m>, 
                  and <m>n=132</m> we can compute the balance using 
                  <xref ref="eqn-olb-retro"/>. If we use all of those, plus 
                  <m>R=2747.49</m>, we can compute the balance using 
                  <xref ref="eqn-olb-prospective"/>: $453,219.98.
                </p>
                <p>
                  This will be our new loan amount. As we begin seeking
                  our new level payments, we use 
                  <xref ref="eqn-loan-level-payment"/>
                  with the new rate, term, and loan amount: 
                  <m>i=\frac{0.045}{12}, N=12(29)=348, L=453219.98</m>.
                  This will provide the new monthly payment of $2334.05.
                  The final payment can be found as the amount
                  that will make the present value of it and all the
                  other payments equal to the new loan amount.
                  We can use <xref ref="eqn-pv-many-future-payments"/>
                  to find the present value of all but the last 
                  payment. That final payment, which we can call 
                  <m>R</m>, must be valued all the way back at the
                  beginning of this new loan, and for this sort of
                  backward movement through time remember that we
                  divide by powers of <m>(1+i)</m>. So for us, in 
                  this case, the present value of the final payment
                  is:
                  <me>
                    \dfrac{R}{(1+i)^N}=\dfrac{R}{(1+\frac{0.045}{12})^{348}}
                  </me>
                </p>
              </solution>
            </example>
            <p>
              The previous example shows the most common use of 
              refinancing a loan. But there are other reasons one 
              might wish to refinance: gaining more money in the
              present, for example to have money to make home 
              improvements, or to shorten the term for paying off
              all of the debt.
            </p>
            <example>
              <title>
                Refinancing with a Lower Interest Rate: Money for Home Improvement
              </title>
              <statement>
                <p>

                </p>
              </statement>
              <answer>
                <p>
