      <chapter xml:id="ch-probability">
        <title>How Likely is Some Occurrence?</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Now that we are becoming more comfortable with percentages 
            and proportions, why not think about a
            proportion of the time that something happens? It isn't 
            that different, conceptually, to say that 65%
            of some group of 100 people have brown eyes as it is to 
            say that 65% of the 100 days from February 14
            to May 25 have some rain that falls on Seattle at some 
            point during that day.
          </p>
          <p>
            The trick as we begin wading into these waters is to 
            do so with a bit of a sense of wonder and play. Some of
            the early examples will feel almost trivial, often 
            descriptions of frivolous games of various sorts. The
            beauty of this is, though, that the principles and 
            practices we learn in these simple contexts can scale
            up to give us insight on rather complex and surprising
            applications later. 
          </p>
          <p>
            With this in mind, perhaps it is easier to suspend  
            impatience or eye-rolling impulses. Try, if you can,
            to just enjoy the game-like explorations near the start.
            But before we do that, a brief historical perspective.
          </p>
        </introduction>


