      <chapter xml:id="ch-marx-models">
        <title>Marx and his Mathematical Models</title>
        <p>
          The brilliant philosophical and economic thinker, Karl Marx, 
          is one of the most influential 
          minds over the last two centuries, especially in our 
          understanding of the current dominant world
          economic system, capitalism. While it is beyond the 
          scope of this textbook to debate whether Marx
          was right or not (in itself a strange debate, generally 
          driven by ideology rather than honest desire
          for truth) instead we will focus on Marx's clever 
          deployment of mathematical models to help drive
          insight for himself and understanding for others. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Marx was faced with a problem: he saw the dynamic creative potential 
          within capitalism, yet he also clearly saw
          (in a way that far too many self-interested capital boosters now do not) 
          the enormous violence 
          this economic system visited upon those who performed the vast 
          majority of the hazardous and back-breaking
          labor within it. In the face of many theorists before and since, 
          Marx sought a mode of analysis that would
          not only explain the movement of capital and the deployment 
          of labor power, but also might generate
          insights about instability within the system and long-term tendencies. 
          All of this, he is carrying out very 
          near the birth of capitalism and in the context of its early 
          working out of its principles and practices.
        </p>
      </chapter>

      <chapter xml:id="ch-statistics">
        <title>Statistics: Summarizing and Hypothesizing</title>
        
        <section> 
          <title>A Dizzyingly Complex World</title>
          <p>
            A beautiful reality is that we inhabit a 
            universe that is boundlessly complex,
            filled with processes and orders that we 
            have only barely begun to understand. 
            One cannot get very far into the scientific 
            world without hearing a lot about
            statistics, and so we will begin to explore 
            them here.   
          </p>
          <p>
            The key idea for statistics is this: given that our ways of measuring reality
            are many, and given that many groups of objects or phenomena that we might 
            wish to measure and understand are quite numerous, how can we grasp patterns
            or tendencies within these groups? As humans, we have a very limited ability
            to recognize patterns or tendencies from within a huge list of numbers. We 
            simply did not evolve to have intuition for that sort of thing. The field we 
            call <q>statistics</q> is designed precisely to give us methods of summarizing
            and understanding tendencies within groups of objects.
          </p>
          <example>
            <p> 
              Suppose we wished to understand a certain variety of penguin inhabiting
              southerly islands at some point in time. We might wish to undestand the size
              of the adult penguins. Now, size might be measured in a variety of ways: length,
              mass, circumference of head, circumference of torso. 
            </p>
            <p>
              
            </p>
          </example>
        </section>
